# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: magnetic-core
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] An **AC motor** is an electric motor driven by an alternating current (AC).
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The AC motor commonly consists of two basic parts, an outside stator having coils supplied with alternating current to produce a rotating magnetic field, and an inside rotor attached to the output shaft producing a second rotating magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The rotor magnetic field may be produced by permanent magnets, reluctance saliency, or DC or AC electrical windings.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Less common, AC linear motors operate on similar principles as rotating motors but have their stationary and moving parts arranged in a straight line configuration, producing linear motion instead of rotation.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The two main types of AC motors are induction motors and synchronous motors.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The induction motor (or asynchronous motor) always relies on a small difference in speed between the stator rotating magnetic field and the rotor shaft speed called slip to induce rotor current in the rotor AC winding.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] As a result, the induction motor cannot produce torque near synchronous speed where induction (or slip) is irrelevant or ceases to exist.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] In contrast, the synchronous motor does not rely on slip-induction for operation and uses either permanent magnets, salient poles (having projecting magnetic poles), or an independently excited rotor winding.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The synchronous motor produces its rated torque at exactly synchronous speed.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The brushless wound-rotor doubly fed synchronous motor system has an independently excited rotor winding that does not rely on the principles of slip-induction of current.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The brushless wound-rotor doubly fed motor is a synchronous motor that can function exactly at the supply frequency or sub to super multiple of the supply frequency.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Other types of motors include eddy current motors, and AC and DC mechanically commutated machines in which speed is dependent on voltage and winding connection.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Alternating current technology was rooted in Michael Faraday's and Joseph Henry's 1830–31 discovery that a changing magnetic field can induce an electric current in a circuit.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Faraday is usually given credit for this discovery since he published his findings first.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] In 1832, French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii generated a crude form of alternating current when he designed and built the first alternator.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] It consisted of a revolving horseshoe magnet passing over two wound-wire coils.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Because of AC's advantages in long-distance high voltage transmission, there were many inventors in the United States and Europe during the late 19th century trying to develop workable AC motors.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The first person to conceive of a rotating magnetic field was Walter Baily, who gave a workable demonstration of his battery-operated polyphase motor aided by a commutator on 28 June 1879, to the Physical Society of London.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Describing an apparatus nearly identical to Baily's, French electrical engineer Marcel Deprez published a paper in 1880 that identified the rotating magnetic field principle and that of a two-phase AC system of currents to produce it.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Never practically demonstrated, the design was flawed, as one of the two currents was “furnished by the machine itself.” In 1886, English-born American engineer Elihu Thomson built an AC motor by expanding upon the induction-repulsion principle and his wattmeter.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] In 1887, American inventor Charles Schenk Bradley was the first to patent a two-phase AC power transmission with four wires.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] "Commutatorless" alternating current induction motors seem to have been independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] In 1888, Ferraris published his research to the Royal Academy of Sciences in Turin, where he detailed the foundations of motor operation; Tesla, in the same year, was granted a United States patent for his own motor.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Working from Ferraris's experiments, Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky introduced the first three-phase induction motor in 1890, a much more capable design that became the prototype used in Europe and the U.S.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] He also invented the first three-phase generator and transformer and combined them into the first complete AC three-phase system in 1891.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The three-phase motor design was also worked on by the Swiss engineer Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown, and other three-phase AC systems were developed by German technician Friedrich August Haselwander and Swedish engineer Jonas Wenström.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] If the rotor of a squirrel cage motor were to run at the true synchronous speed, the flux in the rotor at any given place on the rotor would not change, and no current would be created in the squirrel cage.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] For this reason, ordinary squirrel-cage motors run at some tens of revolutions per minute (RPM) slower than synchronous speed.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Because the rotating field (or equivalent pulsating field) effectively rotates faster than the rotor, it could be said to *slip* past the surface of the rotor.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The difference between synchronous speed and actual speed is called **slip**, and loading the motor increases the amount of slip as the motor slows down slightly.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Even with no load, internal mechanical losses prevent the slip from being zero.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The constant 120 results from combining the conversions of 60 seconds per minute and that each phase requires 2 poles.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Actual RPM for an induction motor will be less than this calculated synchronous speed by an amount known as *slip*, that increases with the torque produced.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] With no load, the speed will be very close to synchronous.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] When loaded, standard motors have between 2–3% slip, special motors may have up to 7% slip, and a class of motors known as *torque motors* are rated to operate at 100% slip (i.e., 0 rpm, full stall).
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] As an example, a typical four-pole motor running on 60 Hz might have a nameplate rating of 1725 rpm at full load, while its calculated speed is 1800 rpm.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The speed in this type of motor has traditionally been altered by having additional sets of coils or poles in the motor that can be switched on and off to change the speed of magnetic field rotation.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] However, developments in power electronics mean that the frequency of the power supply can also now be varied to provide a smoother control of the motor speed.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] This kind of rotor is the basic hardware for induction regulators, which is an exception of the use of rotating magnetic field as pure electrical (not electromechanical) application.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Most common AC motors use the squirrel-cage rotor, which will be found in virtually all domestic and light industrial alternating current motors.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The squirrel-cage refers to the rotating exercise cage for pet animals.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The motor takes its name from the shape of its rotor "windings"- a ring at either end of the rotor, with bars connecting the rings running the length of the rotor.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] It is typically cast aluminum or copper poured between the iron laminates of the rotor, and usually only the end rings will be visible.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The vast majority of the rotor currents will flow through the bars rather than the higher-resistance and usually varnished laminates.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Very low voltages at very high currents are typical in the bars and end rings; high efficiency motors will often use cast copper to reduce the resistance in the rotor.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] In operation, the squirrel-cage motor may be viewed as a transformer with a rotating secondary.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] When the rotor is not rotating in sync with the magnetic field, large rotor currents are induced; the large rotor currents magnetize the rotor and interact with the stator's magnetic fields to bring the rotor almost into synchronization with the stator's field.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] An unloaded squirrel-cage motor at rated no-load speed will consume electrical power only to maintain rotor speed against friction and resistance losses.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] As the mechanical load increases, so will the electrical load – the electrical load is inherently related to the mechanical load.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] This is similar to a transformer, where the primary's electrical load is related to the secondary's electrical load.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] This is why a squirrel-cage blower motor may cause household lights to dim upon starting, but does not dim the lights on startup when its fan belt (and therefore mechanical load) is removed.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Furthermore, a stalled squirrel-cage motor (overloaded or with a jammed shaft) will consume current limited only by circuit resistance as it attempts to start.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Unless something else limits the current (or cuts it off completely) overheating and destruction of the winding insulation is the likely outcome.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Many washing machines, dishwashers, larger standalone fans, compressors, etc. use some variant of a squirrel-cage motor.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] An alternate design, called the wound rotor motor, is used when variable speed is required.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] In this case, the rotor has the same number of poles as the stator and the windings are made of wire, connected to slip rings on the shaft.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Carbon brushes connect the slip rings to a controller such as a variable resistor that allows changing the motor's slip rate.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] In certain high-power variable-speed wound rotor drives, the slip-frequency energy is captured, rectified, and returned to the power supply through an inverter.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] With bidirectionally controlled power, the wound rotor becomes an active participant in the energy conversion process, with the wound rotor doubly fed configuration showing twice the power density.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Compared to squirrel cage rotors, wound rotor motors are expensive and require maintenance of the slip rings and brushes, but they were the standard form for variable speed control before the advent of compact power electronic devices.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Transistorized inverters with variable-frequency drive can now be used for speed control, and wound rotor motors are becoming less common.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Several methods of starting a polyphase motor are used.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Where a large inrush current and high starting torque can be permitted, the motor can be started across the line, by applying full line voltage to the terminals (direct-on-line, DOL).
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Where it is necessary to limit the starting inrush current (where the motor is large compared with the short-circuit capacity of the supply), the motor is started at reduced voltage using either series inductors, an autotransformer, thyristors, or other devices.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] A technique sometimes used is star-delta (YΔ) starting, where the motor coils are initially connected in star configuration for acceleration of the load, then switched to delta configuration when the load is up to speed.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] This technique is more common in Europe than in North America.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Transistorized drives can directly vary the applied voltage as required by the starting characteristics of the motor and load.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] This type of motor is becoming more common in traction applications such as locomotives, where it is known as the asynchronous traction motor.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] 2. a control-voltage (AC) winding in quadrature (i.e., 90 degrees phase shifted) with the main winding so as to produce a rotating magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Reversing phase makes the motor reverse.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] An AC servo amplifier, a linear power amplifier, feeds the control winding.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The electrical resistance of the rotor is made high intentionally so that the speed–torque curve is fairly linear.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Two-phase servo motors are inherently high-speed, low-torque devices, heavily geared down to drive the load.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Single-phase motors do not have a unique rotating magnetic field like multi-phase motors.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The field alternates (reverses polarity) between pole pairs and can be viewed as two fields rotating in opposite directions.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] They require a secondary magnetic field that causes the rotor to move in a specific direction.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] After starting, the alternating stator field is in relative rotation with the rotor.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] A common single-phase motor is the shaded-pole motor and is used in devices requiring low starting torque, such as electric fans, small pumps, or small household appliances.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] In this motor, small single-turn copper "shading coils" create the moving magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Part of each pole is encircled by a copper coil or strap; the induced current in the strap opposes the change of flux through the coil.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] This causes a time lag in the flux passing through the shading coil, so that the maximum field intensity moves higher across the pole face on each cycle.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] This produces a low level rotating magnetic field which is large enough to turn both the rotor and its attached load.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] As the rotor picks up speed the torque builds up to its full level as the principal magnetic field is rotating relative to the rotating rotor.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] A **reversible shaded-pole motor** was made by Barber-Colman several decades ago.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] It had a single field coil, and two principal poles, each split halfway to create two pairs of poles.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Each of these four "half-poles" carried a coil, and the coils of diagonally opposite half-poles were connected to a pair of terminals.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] One terminal of each pair was common, so only three terminals were needed in all.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The motor would not start with the terminals open; connecting the common to one made the motor run one way, and connecting the common to the other made it run the other way.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] These motors were used in industrial and scientific devices.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] An unusual, **adjustable-speed**, low-torque shaded-pole motor could be found in traffic-light and advertising-lighting controllers.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The pole faces were parallel and relatively close to each other, with the disc centered between them, something like the disc in a watthour electricity meter.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Each pole face was split, and had a shading coil on one part; the shading coils were on the parts that faced each other.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Applying AC to the coil created a field that progressed in the gap between the poles.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The plane of the stator core was approximately tangential to an imaginary circle on the disc, so the travelling magnetic field dragged the disc and made it rotate.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The stator was mounted on a pivot so it could be positioned for the desired speed and then clamped in position.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Placing the poles nearer to the center of the disc made it run faster, and toward the edge, slower.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Another common single-phase AC motor is the *split-phase induction motor*, commonly used in major appliances such as air conditioners and clothes dryers.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Compared to the shaded pole motor, these motors provide much greater starting torque.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] A split-phase motor has a secondary startup winding that is 90 electrical degrees to the main winding, always centered directly between the poles of the main winding, and connected to the main winding by a set of electrical contacts.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The coils of this winding are wound with fewer turns of smaller wire than the main winding, so it has a lower inductance and higher resistance.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The position of the winding creates a small phase shift between the flux of the main winding and the flux of the starting winding, causing the rotor to rotate.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] When the speed of the motor is sufficient to overcome the inertia of the load, the contacts are opened automatically by a centrifugal switch or electric relay.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The direction of rotation is determined by the connection between the main winding and the start circuit.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] In applications where the motor requires a fixed rotation, one end of the start circuit is permanently connected to the main winding, with the contacts making the connection at the other end.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] A capacitor start motor is a split-phase induction motor with a starting motor capacitor inserted in series with the startup winding, creating an LC circuit which produces a greater phase shift (and so, a much greater starting torque) than both split-phase and shaded pole motors.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] This motor has a centrifugal switch which disconnects the capacitor once the motor has started.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] This motor provides high starting torque.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] This motor provides high starting torque and high efficiency.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] A resistance start motor is a split-phase induction motor with a starter inserted in series with the startup winding, creating reactance.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] This added starter provides assistance in the starting and initial direction of rotation.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The start winding is made mainly of thin wire with fewer turns to make it high resistive and less inductive.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The main winding is made with thicker wire with larger number of turns which makes it less resistive and more inductive.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Another variation is the *permanent-split capacitor (or PSC) motor*.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Also known as a capacitor-run motor, this type of motor uses a non-polarized capacitor with a high voltage rating to generate an electrical phase shift between the run and start windings.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] PSC motors are the dominant type of split-phase motor in Europe and much of the world, but in North America, they are most frequently used in variable torque applications (like blowers, fans, and pumps) and other cases where variable speeds are desired.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] A capacitor with a relatively low capacitance, and relatively high voltage rating, is connected in series with the start winding and remains in the circuit during the entire run cycle.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Like other split-phase motors, the main winding is used with a smaller start winding, and rotation is changed by reversing the connection between the main winding and the start circuit, or by having polarity of main winding switched while start winding is always connected to a capacitor.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] There are significant differences, however; the use of a speed sensitive centrifugal switch requires that other split-phase motors must operate at, or very close to, full speed.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] PSC motors may operate within a wide range of speeds, much lower than the motor's electrical speed.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Also, for applications like automatic door openers that require the motor to reverse rotation often, the use of a mechanism requires that a motor must slow to a near stop before contact with the start winding is re-established.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The 'permanent' connection to the capacitor in a PSC motor means that changing rotation is instantaneous.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Three-phase motors can be converted to PSC motors by making common two windings and connecting the third via a capacitor to act as a start winding.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] However, the power rating needs to be at least 50% larger than for a comparable single-phase motor due to an unused winding.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The synchronous motor can also be used as an alternator.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Contemporary synchronous motors are frequently driven by solid state variable-frequency drives.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] This greatly eases the problem of starting the massive rotor of a large synchronous motor.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Synchronous motors are occasionally used as traction motors; the TGV may be the best-known example of such use.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Huge numbers of three phase synchronous motors are now fitted to electric cars.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] They have a neodymium or other rare-earth permanent magnet.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] One use for this type of motor is its use in a power factor correction scheme.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] They are referred to as synchronous condensers.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] This exploits a feature of the machine where it consumes power at a leading power factor when its rotor is over excited.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] It thus appears to the supply to be a capacitor, and could thus be used to correct the lagging power factor that is usually presented to the electric supply by inductive loads.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The excitation is adjusted until a near unity power factor is obtained (often automatically).
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Machines used for this purpose are easily identified as they have no shaft extensions.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Synchronous motors are valued in any case because their power factor is much better than that of induction motors, making them preferred for very high power applications.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Some of the largest AC motors are pumped-storage hydroelectricity generators that are operated as synchronous motors to pump water to a reservoir at a higher elevation for later use to generate electricity using the same machinery.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Six 500-megawatt generators are installed in the Bath County Pumped Storage Station in Virginia, USA.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] When pumping, each unit can produce 642,800 horsepower (479.3 megawatts).
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Small single-phase AC motors can also be designed with magnetized rotors (or several variations on that idea; see "Hysteresis synchronous motors" below).
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] If a conventional squirrel-cage rotor has flats ground on it to create salient poles and increase reluctance, it will start conventionally, but will run synchronously, although it can provide only a modest torque at synchronous speed.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Because inertia makes it difficult to instantly accelerate the rotor from stopped to synchronous speed, these motors normally require some sort of special feature to get started.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Some include a squirrel-cage structure to bring the rotor close to synchronous speed.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Various other designs use a small induction motor (which may share the same field coils and rotor as the synchronous motor) or a very light rotor with a one-way mechanism (to ensure that the rotor starts in the "forward" direction).
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] In the latter instance, applying AC power creates chaotic (or seemingly chaotic) jumping movement back and forth; such a motor will always start, but lacking the anti-reversal mechanism, the direction it runs is unpredictable.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The Hammond organ tone generator used a non-self-starting synchronous motor (until comparatively recently), and had an auxiliary conventional shaded-pole starting motor.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] A spring-loaded auxiliary manual starting switch connected power to this second motor for a few seconds.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] These motors are relatively costly, and are used where exact speed (assuming an exact-frequency AC source) and rotation with low flutter (high-frequency variation in speed) are essential.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Applications included tape recorder capstan drives (the motor shaft could be the capstan), and, before the advent of crystal control, motion picture cameras and recorders.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Their distinguishing feature is their rotor, which is a smooth cylinder of a magnetic alloy that stays magnetized, but can be demagnetized fairly easily as well as re-magnetized with poles in a new location.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Hysteresis refers to how the magnetic flux in the metal lags behind the external magnetizing force; for instance, to demagnetize such a material, one could apply a magnetizing field of opposite polarity to that which originally magnetized the material.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] These motors have a stator like those of capacitor-run squirrel-cage induction motors.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] On startup, when slip decreases sufficiently, the rotor becomes magnetized by the stator's field, and the poles stay in place.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The motor then runs at synchronous speed as if the rotor were a permanent magnet.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] When stopped and restarted, the poles are likely to form at different locations.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] For a given design, torque at synchronous speed is only relatively modest, and the motor can run at below synchronous speed.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] In simple words, it is lagging magnetic field behind magnetic flux.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] A universal motor is a design that can operate on either AC or DC power.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] In universal motors the stator and rotor of a brushed DC motor are both wound and supplied from an external source, with the torque being a function of the rotor current times the stator current so reversing the current in both rotor and stator does not reverse the rotation.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Universal motors can run on AC as well as DC provided the frequency is not so high that the inductive reactance of the stator winding and eddy current losses become problems.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Nearly all universal motors are series-wound because their stators have relatively few turns, minimizing inductance.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Universal motors are compact, have high starting torque and can be varied in speed over a wide range with relatively simple controls such as rheostats and PWM choppers.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Compared with induction motors, universal motors do have some drawbacks inherent to their brushes and commutators: relatively high levels of electrical and acoustic noise, low reliability and more frequent required maintenance.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Universal motors are widely used in small home appliances and hand power tools.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Until the 1970s they dominated electric traction (electric, including diesel-electric railway and road vehicles); many traction power networks still use special low frequencies such as 16.7 and 25 Hz to overcome the aforementioned problems with losses and reactance.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Still widely used, universal traction motors have been increasingly displaced by polyphase AC induction and permanent magnet motors with variable-frequency drives made possible by modern power semiconductor devices.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Repulsion motors are wound-rotor single-phase AC motors that are a type of induction motor.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] In a repulsion motor, the armature brushes are shorted together rather than connected in series with the field, as is done with universal motors.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] By transformer action, the stator induces currents in the rotor, which create torque by repulsion instead of attraction as in other motors.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Several types of repulsion motors have been manufactured, but the *repulsion-start induction-run* (RS-IR) motor has been used most frequently.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The RS-IR motor has a centrifugal switch that shorts all segments of the commutator so that the motor operates as an induction motor once it is close to full speed.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Some of these motors also lift the brushes out of contact with source voltage regulation.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Repulsion motors were developed before suitable motor starting capacitors were available, and few repulsion motors are sold as of 2005.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Where speed stability is important, some AC motors (such as some Papst motors) have the stator on the inside and the rotor on the outside to optimize inertia and cooling.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Exterior rotors are also common in ceiling fan motors.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] A conical rotor brake motor incorporates the brake as an integral part of the conical sliding rotor.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] When the motor is at rest, a spring acts on the sliding rotor and forces the brake ring against the brake cap in the motor, holding the rotor stationary.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] When the motor is energized, its magnetic field generates both an axial and a radial component.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The axial component overcomes the spring force, releasing the brake; while the radial component causes the rotor to turn.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] There is no additional brake control required.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The high starting torque and low inertia of the conical rotor brake motor has proven to be ideal for the demands of high cycle dynamic drives in applications since the motor was invented, designed and introduced over 50 years ago.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] This type of motor configuration was first introduced in the US in 1963.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Single-speed or two speed motors are designed for coupling to gear motor system gearboxes.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Conical rotor brake motors are also used to power micro speed drives.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Motors of this type can also be found on overhead cranes and hoists.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The micro speed unit combines two motors and an intermediate gear reducer.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] These are used for applications where extreme mechanical positioning accuracy and high cycling capability are needed.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The micro speed unit combines a “main” conical rotor brake motor for rapid speed and a “micro” conical rotor brake motor for slow or positioning speed.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The intermediate gearbox allows a range of ratios, and motors of different speeds can be combined to produce high ratios between high and low speed.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Electronically commutated (EC) motors are electric motors powered by direct-current (DC) electricity and having electronic commutation systems, rather than mechanical commutators and brushes.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The current-to-torque and frequency-to-speed relationships of BLDC motors are linear.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] While the motor coils are powered by DC, power may be rectified from AC within the casing.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] These are two-phase induction motors with permanent magnets to retard the rotor so its speed is accurately proportional to the power passing through the meter.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The rotor is an aluminium-alloy disc, and currents induced into it react with the field from the stator.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] A split-phase watthour electricity meter has a stator with three coils facing the disc.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The magnetic circuit is completed by a C-shaped core of permeable iron.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The "voltage" coil above the disc is in parallel with the supply; its many turns have a high inductance/resistance ratio (Q) so its current and magnetic field are the time integral of the applied voltage, lagging it by 90 degrees.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] This magnetic field passes down perpendicularly through the disc, inducing circular eddy currents in the plane of the disc centered on the field.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] These induced currents are proportional to the time derivative of the magnetic field, leading it by 90 degrees.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] This puts the eddy currents in phase with the voltage applied to the voltage coil, just as the current induced in the secondary of a transformer with a resistive load is in phase with the voltage applied to its primary.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The eddy currents pass directly above the pole pieces of two "current" coils under the disc, each wound with a few turns of heavy-gauge wire whose inductive reactance is small compared to the load impedance.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] These coils connect the supply to the load, producing a magnetic field in phase with the load current.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] This field passes from the pole of one current coil up perpendicularly through the disc and back down through the disc to the pole of the other current coil, with a completed magnetic circuit back to the first current coil.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] As these fields cross the disc, they pass through the eddy currents induced in it by the voltage coil producing a Lorentz force on the disc mutually perpendicular to both.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Assuming power is flowing to the load, the flux from the left current coil crosses the disc upwards where the eddy current flows radially toward the center of the disc producing (by the right-hand rule) a torque driving the front of the disc to the right.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Similarly, the flux crosses down through the disc to the right current coil where the eddy current flows radially away from the disc center, again producing a torque driving the front of the disc to the right.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] When the AC polarity reverses, the eddy currents in the disc and the direction of the magnetic flux from the current coils both change, leaving the direction of the torque unchanged.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The torque is thus proportional to the instantaneous line voltage times the instantaneous load current, automatically correcting for power factor.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The disc is braked by a permanent magnet so that speed is proportional to torque and the disc mechanically integrates real power.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The mechanical dial on the meter reads disc rotations and the total net energy delivered to the load.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] In a split-phase watthour meter the voltage coil is connected between the two "hot" (line) terminals (240 V in North America) and two separate current coils are connected between the corresponding line and load terminals.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] No connection to the system neutral is needed to correctly handle combined line-to-neutral and line-to-line loads.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Line-to-line loads draw the same current through both current coils and spin the meter twice as fast as a line-to-neutral load drawing the same current through only a single current coil, correctly registering the power drawn by the line-to-line load as twice that of the line-to-neutral load.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Other variations of the same design are used for polyphase (e.g., three-phase) power.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Representative are low-torque synchronous motors with a multi-pole hollow cylindrical magnet (internal poles) surrounding the stator structure.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The stator has one coil, coaxial with the shaft.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] At each end of the coil are a pair of circular plates with rectangular teeth on their edges, formed so they are parallel with the shaft.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] One of the pair of discs distributes the coil's flux directly, while the other receives flux that has passed through a common shading coil.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] The poles are rather narrow, and between the poles leading from one end of the coil are an identical set leading from the other end.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] In all, this creates a repeating sequence of four poles, unshaded alternating with shaded, that creates a circumferential traveling field to which the rotor's magnetic poles rapidly synchronize.
[src:magnetic-core/ac-motor] Some stepping motors have a similar structure.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The **atmosphere of Earth** consists of a layer of mixed gas (commonly referred to as **air**) that is retained by gravity, surrounding the Earth's surface.
[src:magnetic-core/air] It contains variable quantities of suspended aerosols and particulates that create weather features such as clouds and hazes.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The atmosphere serves as a protective buffer between the Earth's surface and outer space.
[src:magnetic-core/air] It shields the surface from most meteoroids and ultraviolet solar radiation, reduces diurnal temperature variation – the temperature extremes between day and night, and keeps it warm through heat retention via the greenhouse effect.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The atmosphere redistributes heat and moisture among different regions via air currents, and provides the chemical and climate conditions that allow life to exist and evolve on Earth.
[src:magnetic-core/air] By mole fraction (i.e., by quantity of molecules), dry air contains 78.08% nitrogen, 20.95% oxygen, 0.93% argon, 0.04% carbon dioxide, and small amounts of other trace gases (see Composition below for more detail).
[src:magnetic-core/air] Air also contains a variable amount of water vapor, on average around 1% at sea level, and 0.4% over the entire atmosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Earth's primordial atmosphere consisted of gases accreted from the solar nebula, but the composition changed significantly over time, affected by many factors such as volcanism, outgassing, impact events, weathering and the evolution of life (particularly the photoautotrophs).
[src:magnetic-core/air] In the present day, human activity has contributed to atmospheric changes, such as climate change (mainly through deforestation and fossil-fuel–related global warming), ozone depletion and acid deposition.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The atmosphere has a mass of about 5.15×1018 kg, three quarters of which is within about 11 km (6.8 mi; 36,000 ft) of the surface.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The atmosphere becomes thinner with increasing altitude, with no definite boundary between the atmosphere and outer space.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The Kármán line at 100 km (62 mi) is often used as a conventional definition of the edge of space.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Several layers can be distinguished in the atmosphere based on characteristics such as temperature and composition, namely the troposphere, stratosphere, mesosphere, thermosphere (formally the ionosphere), and exosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Air composition, temperature and atmospheric pressure vary with altitude.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Air suitable for use in photosynthesis by terrestrial plants and respiration of terrestrial animals is found within the troposphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The study of Earth's atmosphere and its processes is called atmospheric science (aerology), and includes multiple subfields, such as climatology and atmospheric physics.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Early pioneers in the field include Léon Teisserenc de Bort and Richard Assmann.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The study of the historic atmosphere is called paleoclimatology.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The three major constituents of Earth's atmosphere are nitrogen, oxygen, and argon.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Water vapor accounts for roughly 0.25% of the atmosphere by mass.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The remaining gases are often referred to as trace gases, among which are other greenhouse gases, principally carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, and ozone.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Besides argon, other noble gases, neon, helium, krypton, and xenon are also present.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Filtered air includes trace amounts of many other chemical compounds.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Many substances of natural origin may be present in locally and seasonally variable small amounts as aerosols in an unfiltered air sample, including dust of mineral and organic composition, pollen and spores, sea spray, and volcanic ash.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Various industrial pollutants also may be present as gases or aerosols, such as chlorine (elemental or in compounds), fluorine compounds, and elemental mercury vapor.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Sulfur compounds such as hydrogen sulfide and sulfur dioxide (SO2) may be derived from natural sources or from industrial air pollution.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The average molecular weight of dry air, which can be used to calculate densities or to convert between mole fraction and mass fraction, is about 28.946 or 28.964 g/mol.
[src:magnetic-core/air] This is decreased when the air is humid.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Up to an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi), atmospheric turbulence mixes the component gases so that their relative concentrations remain the same.
[src:magnetic-core/air] There exists a transition zone from roughly 80 to 120 km (50 to 75 mi) where this turbulent mixing gradually yields to molecular diffusion.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The latter process forms the heterosphere where the relative concentration of lighter gases increase with altitude.
[src:magnetic-core/air] In general, air pressure and density decrease with altitude in the atmosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] However, temperature has a more complicated profile with altitude and may remain relatively constant or even increase with altitude in some regions (see the temperature section).
[src:magnetic-core/air] Because the general pattern of the temperature/altitude profile, or lapse rate, is constant and measurable by means of instrumented balloon soundings, the temperature behavior provides a useful metric to distinguish atmospheric layers.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The exosphere is the outermost layer of Earth's atmosphere (though it is so tenuous that some scientists consider it to be part of interplanetary space rather than part of the atmosphere).
[src:magnetic-core/air] It extends from the thermopause (also known as the "exobase") at the top of the thermosphere to a poorly defined boundary with the solar wind and interplanetary medium.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The altitude of the exobase varies from about 500 kilometres (310 mi; 1,600,000 ft) to about 1,000 kilometres (620 mi) in times of higher incoming solar radiation.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The upper limit varies depending on the definition.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Various authorities consider it to end at about 10,000 kilometres (6,200 mi) or about 190,000 kilometres (120,000 mi)—about halfway to the moon, where the influence of Earth's gravity is about the same as radiation pressure from sunlight.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The geocorona visible in the far ultraviolet (caused by neutral hydrogen) extends to at least 100,000 kilometres (62,000 mi).
[src:magnetic-core/air] This layer is mainly composed of extremely low densities of hydrogen, with limited amounts of helium, carbon dioxide, and nascent oxygen closer to the exobase.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The atoms and molecules are so far apart that they can travel hundreds of kilometres without colliding with one another.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Thus, the exosphere no longer behaves like a gas, and the particles constantly escape into space.
[src:magnetic-core/air] These free-moving particles follow ballistic trajectories and may migrate in and out of the magnetosphere or the solar wind.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Every second, the Earth loses about 3 kg of hydrogen, 50 g of helium, and much smaller amounts of other constituents.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The exosphere is too far above Earth for meteorological phenomena to be possible.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The exosphere contains many of the artificial satellites that orbit Earth.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The thermosphere is the second-highest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] It extends from the mesopause (which separates it from the mesosphere) at an altitude of about 80 km (50 mi) up to the thermopause at an altitude range of 500–1000 km (310–620 mi).
[src:magnetic-core/air] The height of the thermopause varies considerably due to changes in solar activity.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The passage of the dusk and dawn solar terminator creates background density perturbations up to a factor of two through this layer, forming a dominant feature in this region.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Because the thermopause lies at the lower boundary of the exosphere, it is also referred to as the exobase.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Overlapping the thermosphere, from 50 to 600 kilometres (31 to 373 mi) above Earth's surface, is the ionosphere – a region of enhanced plasma density.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The temperature of the thermosphere gradually increases with height and can rise as high as 1500 °C (2700 °F), though the gas molecules are so far apart that its temperature in the usual sense is not very meaningful.
[src:magnetic-core/air] This temperature increase is caused by absorption of ionizing UV and X-ray emission from the Sun.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The air is so rarefied that an individual molecule (of oxygen, for example) travels an average of 1 kilometre (0.62 mi; 3300 ft) between collisions with other molecules.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Although the thermosphere has a high proportion of molecules with high energy, it would not feel hot to a human in direct contact, because its density is too low to conduct a significant amount of energy to or from the skin.
[src:magnetic-core/air] This layer is completely cloudless and free of water vapor.
[src:magnetic-core/air] However, non-hydrometeorological phenomena such as the aurora borealis and aurora australis are occasionally seen in the thermosphere at an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi).
[src:magnetic-core/air] The colors of the aurora are linked to the properties of the atmosphere at the altitude they occur.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The most common is the green aurora, which comes from atomic oxygen in the 1S state, and occurs at altitudes from 120 to 400 km (75 to 250 mi).
[src:magnetic-core/air] The International Space Station orbits in the thermosphere, between 370 and 460 km (230 and 290 mi).
[src:magnetic-core/air] It is this layer where many of the satellites orbiting the Earth are present.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The mesosphere is the third highest layer of Earth's atmosphere, occupying the region above the stratosphere and below the thermosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] It extends from the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 km (31 mi) to the mesopause at 80–85 km (50–53 mi) above sea level.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Temperatures drop with increasing altitude to the mesopause that marks the top of this middle layer of the atmosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] It is the coldest place on Earth and has an average temperature around −85 °C (−120 °F; 190 K).
[src:magnetic-core/air] Because the atmosphere absorbs sound waves at a rate that is proportional to the square of the frequency, audible sounds from the ground do not reach the mesosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Infrasonic waves can reach this altitude, but they are difficult to emit at a high power level.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Just below the mesopause, the air is so cold that even the very scarce water vapor at this altitude can condense into polar-mesospheric noctilucent clouds of ice particles.
[src:magnetic-core/air] These are the highest clouds in the atmosphere and may be visible to the naked eye if sunlight reflects off them about an hour or two after sunset or similarly before sunrise.
[src:magnetic-core/air] They are most readily visible when the Sun is around 4 to 16 degrees below the horizon.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Lightning-induced discharges known as transient luminous events (TLEs) occasionally form in the mesosphere above tropospheric thunderclouds.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The mesosphere is also the layer where most meteors and satellites burn up upon atmospheric entrance.
[src:magnetic-core/air] It is too high above Earth to be accessible to jet-powered aircraft and balloons, and too low to permit orbital spacecraft.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The mesosphere is mainly accessed by sounding rockets and rocket-powered aircraft.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The stratosphere is the second-lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] It lies above the troposphere and is separated from it by the tropopause.
[src:magnetic-core/air] This layer extends from the top of the troposphere at roughly 12 km (7.5 mi) above Earth's surface to the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 to 55 km (31 to 34 mi).
[src:magnetic-core/air] 99% of the total mass of the atmosphere lies below 30 km (19 mi), and the atmospheric pressure at the top of the stratosphere is roughly 1/1000 the pressure at sea level.
[src:magnetic-core/air] It contains the ozone layer, which is the part of Earth's atmosphere that contains relatively high concentrations of that gas.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The stratosphere defines a layer in which temperatures rise with increasing altitude.
[src:magnetic-core/air] This rise in temperature is caused by the absorption of ultraviolet radiation (UV) from the Sun by the ozone layer, which restricts turbulence and mixing.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Although the temperature may be −80 °C (−110 °F; 190 K) at the tropopause, the top of the stratosphere is much warmer, and may be just below 0 °C.
[src:magnetic-core/air] This layer is unique to the Earth; neither Mars nor Venus have a stratosphere because of low abundances of oxygen in their atmospheres.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The stratospheric temperature profile creates very stable atmospheric conditions, so the stratosphere lacks the weather-producing air turbulence that is so prevalent in the troposphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Consequently, the stratosphere is almost completely free of clouds and other forms of weather.
[src:magnetic-core/air] However, polar stratospheric or nacreous clouds are occasionally seen in the lower part of this layer of the atmosphere where the air is coldest.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The stratosphere is the highest layer that can be accessed by jet-powered aircraft.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The troposphere is the lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] It extends from Earth's surface to an average height of about 12 km (7.5 mi), although this altitude varies from about 9 km (5.6 mi) at the geographic poles to 17 km (11 mi) at the Equator, with some variation due to weather.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The troposphere is bounded above by the tropopause, a boundary marked in most places by a temperature inversion (i.e. a layer of relatively warm air above a colder one), and in others by a zone that is isothermal with height.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Although variations do occur, the temperature usually declines with increasing altitude in the troposphere because the troposphere is mostly heated through energy transfer from the surface.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Thus, the lowest part of the troposphere (i.e.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Earth's surface) is typically the warmest section of the troposphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] This promotes vertical mixing (hence, the origin of its name in the Greek word τρόπος, *tropos*, meaning "turn").
[src:magnetic-core/air] The troposphere contains roughly 80% of the mass of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The troposphere is denser than all its overlying layers because a larger atmospheric weight sits on top of the troposphere and causes it to be more severely compressed.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Fifty percent of the total mass of the atmosphere is located in the lower 5.5 km (3.4 mi) of the troposphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Nearly all atmospheric water vapor or moisture is found in the troposphere, so it is the layer where most of Earth's weather takes place.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The ability of the atmosphere to retain water decreases as the temperature declines, so 90% of the water vapor is held in the lower part of the troposphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] It has basically all the weather-associated cloud genus types generated by active wind circulation, although very tall cumulonimbus thunder clouds can penetrate the tropopause from below and rise into the lower part of the stratosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Most conventional aviation activity takes place in the troposphere, and it is the only layer accessible by propeller-driven aircraft.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Contrails are formed from jet engine water emission at altitudes where the atmospheric temperature is about −53 °C (−63 °F); typically around 7.7 km (4.8 mi) for modern engines.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Above this altitude lies the heterosphere, which includes the exosphere and most of the thermosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Here, the chemical composition varies with altitude.
[src:magnetic-core/air] is large compared with the size of motions that cause mixing.
[src:magnetic-core/air] with the heavier ones, such as oxygen and nitrogen, present only near the bottom of the heterosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The upper part of the heterosphere is composed almost completely of hydrogen, the lightest element.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The average temperature of the atmosphere at Earth's surface is 14 °C (57 °F; 287 K) or 15 °C (59 °F; 288 K), depending on the reference.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The average atmospheric pressure at sea level is defined by the International Standard Atmosphere as 101325 pascals (760.00 Torr; 14.6959 psi; 760.00 mmHg).
[src:magnetic-core/air] This is sometimes referred to as a unit of standard atmospheres (atm).
[src:magnetic-core/air] Total atmospheric mass is 5.1480×1018 kg (1.13494×1019 lb), about 2.5% less than would be inferred from the average sea-level pressure and Earth's area of 51007.2 megahectares, this portion being displaced by Earth's mountainous terrain.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Atmospheric pressure is the total weight of the air above unit area at the point where the pressure is measured.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Thus air pressure varies with location and weather.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Air pressure decreases exponentially with altitude at a rate that depends on the air temperature.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The rate of decrease is determined by a temperature-dependent parameter called the scale height: for each increase in altitude by this height, the pressure decreases by a factor of *e* (the base of natural logarithms, approximately 2.718).
[src:magnetic-core/air] For Earth, this value is typically 5.5 to 6 km for altitudes up to around 80 km (50 mi).
[src:magnetic-core/air] However, the atmosphere is more accurately modeled with a customized equation for each layer that takes gradients of temperature, molecular composition, solar radiation and gravity into account.
[src:magnetic-core/air] At heights over 100 km, the atmosphere is not well mixed, so each chemical species has its own scale height.
[src:magnetic-core/air] At altitudes of 200 to 300 km, the combined scale height is 20 to 30 km.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Even above the Kármán line, significant atmospheric effects such as auroras still occur.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Meteors begin to glow in this region, though the larger ones may not burn up until they penetrate more deeply.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The various layers of Earth's ionosphere, important to HF radio propagation, begin below 100 km and extend beyond 500 km.
[src:magnetic-core/air] By comparison, the International Space Station typically orbit at 370–460 km, within the F-layer of the ionosphere, where they encounter enough atmospheric drag to require reboosts every few months, otherwise orbital decay will occur, resulting in a return to Earth.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Depending on solar activity, satellites can experience noticeable atmospheric drag at altitudes as high as 600–800 km.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Starting at sea level, the temperature decreases with altitude until reaching the stratosphere at around 11 km.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Above, the temperature stabilizes over a large vertical distance.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Starting above about 20 km, the temperature increases with height, due to heating within the ozone layer caused by the capture of significant ultraviolet radiation from the Sun by the molecular oxygen and ozone gas in this region.
[src:magnetic-core/air] A second region of increasing temperature with altitude occurs at very high altitudes, in the aptly-named thermosphere above 90 km.
[src:magnetic-core/air] During the night, the ground radiates more energy than it gains from the atmosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] As energy is conducted from the nearby atmosphere to the cooler ground, it creates a temperature inversion where the local temperature increases with altitude up to around 1,000 m.
[src:magnetic-core/air] For example, at sea level the speed of sound is 340 m/s.
[src:magnetic-core/air] At the average temperature of the stratosphere, −60 °C, the speed of sound decreases to 290 m/s.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Density is not measured directly but is calculated from measurements of temperature, pressure and humidity using the equation of state for air (a form of the ideal gas law).
[src:magnetic-core/air] Atmospheric density decreases as the altitude increases.
[src:magnetic-core/air] This variation can be approximately modeled using the barometric formula.
[src:magnetic-core/air] More sophisticated models are used to predict the orbital decay of satellites.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The average mass of the atmosphere is about 5 quadrillion (5×1015) tonnes or 1/1,200,000 the mass of Earth.
[src:magnetic-core/air] According to the American National Center for Atmospheric Research, "The total mean mass of the atmosphere is 5.1480×1018 kg with an annual range due to water vapor of 1.2 or 1.5×1015 kg, depending on whether surface pressure or water vapor data are used; somewhat smaller than the previous estimate.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Solar radiation (or sunlight) is the energy Earth receives from the Sun.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Earth also emits radiation back into space, but at longer wavelengths that humans cannot see.
[src:magnetic-core/air] As energy propagates through the atmosphere, it is impacted by the process of radiative transfer.
[src:magnetic-core/air] That is, some of the incoming and emitted radiation is subject to absorption, emission, and scattering by the atmosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Another portion of the incident energy is reflected, with the two most important atmospheric reflectors being dust and clouds.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Depending on the properties of the aerosol, clouds can reflect up to 70% of the incident radiation.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Globally, clouds reflect 20% of the incoming energy, contributing two thirds of the planet's total albedo.
[src:magnetic-core/air] In May 2017, glints of light, seen as twinkling from an orbiting satellite a million miles away, were found to be reflected light from ice crystals in the troposphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] When light passes through Earth's atmosphere, photons interact with it through *scattering*.
[src:magnetic-core/air] If the light does not interact with the atmosphere, it is called *direct radiation* and is what you see if you were to look directly at the Sun.
[src:magnetic-core/air] *Indirect radiation* is light that has been scattered in the atmosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] For example, on an overcast day when you cannot see your shadow, there is no direct radiation reaching you, it has all been scattered.
[src:magnetic-core/air] As another example, due to a phenomenon called Rayleigh scattering, shorter (blue) wavelengths scatter more easily than longer (red) wavelengths.
[src:magnetic-core/air] This is why the sky looks blue; you are seeing scattered blue light.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Because the Sun is close to the horizon, the Sun's rays pass through more atmosphere than normal before reaching your eye.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Much of the blue light has been scattered out, leaving the red light in a sunset.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Different molecules absorb different wavelengths of radiation.
[src:magnetic-core/air] For example, O2 and O3 absorb almost all radiation with wavelengths shorter than 300 nanometres.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Water (H2O) absorbs at many wavelengths above 700 nm.
[src:magnetic-core/air] When a molecule absorbs a photon, it increases the energy of the molecule.
[src:magnetic-core/air] This heats the atmosphere, but the atmosphere also cools by emitting radiation, as discussed below.
[src:magnetic-core/air] In astronomical spectroscopy, the absorption of specific frequencies by the atmosphere is referred to as telluric contamination.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The combined absorption spectra of the gases in the atmosphere leave "windows" of low opacity, allowing the transmission of only certain bands of light.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The optical window runs from around 300 nm (ultraviolet-C) up into the range humans can see, the visible spectrum (commonly called light), at roughly 400–700 nm and continues to the infrared to around 1100 nm.
[src:magnetic-core/air] There are also infrared and radio windows that transmit some infrared and radio waves at longer wavelengths.
[src:magnetic-core/air] For example, the radio window runs from about one centimetre to about eleven-metre waves.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Because of its temperature, the atmosphere emits infrared radiation.
[src:magnetic-core/air] For example, on clear nights Earth's surface cools down faster than on cloudy nights.
[src:magnetic-core/air] This is because clouds (H2O) are strong absorbers and emitters of infrared radiation.
[src:magnetic-core/air] This is also why it becomes colder at night at higher elevations.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The greenhouse effect is directly related to this absorption and emission effect.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Some gases in the atmosphere absorb and emit infrared radiation, but do not interact in this manner with sunlight in the visible spectrum.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Common examples of these are CO2 and H2O.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Without greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, the average temperature of Earth's surface would be a frozen −18 °C (0 °F), rather than the present comfortable average of 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:magnetic-core/air] The refractive index of air is close to, but just greater than, 1.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Systematic variations in the refractive index can lead to the bending of light rays over long optical paths.
[src:magnetic-core/air] One example is that, under some circumstances, observers on board ships can see other vessels just over the horizon because light is refracted in the same direction as the curvature of Earth's surface.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The refractive index of air depends on temperature, giving rise to refraction effects when the temperature gradient is large.
[src:magnetic-core/air] An example of such effects is the mirage.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The flow of air around the planet is divided into three main convection cells by latitude.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Around the equator, the Hadley cell is driven by the rising flow of air along the equator.
[src:magnetic-core/air] In the upper atmosphere, this air flows toward the poles.
[src:magnetic-core/air] At mid latitudes, this circulation is reversed, with ground air flowing toward the poles with the Ferrel cell.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Finally, in the high latitudes is the Polar cell, where air again rises and flows toward the poles.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The interface between these cells is responsible for jet streams.
[src:magnetic-core/air] These are narrow, fast moving bands that flow from west to east and typically form at an elevation of around 9,100 m (30,000 ft).
[src:magnetic-core/air] Jet streams can shift around depending on conditions.
[src:magnetic-core/air] They are strongest in winter, when the boundaries between hot and cold air are the most pronounced.
[src:magnetic-core/air] In the middle latitudes, it is instabilities in the jet streams that are responsible for moving weather systems.
[src:magnetic-core/air] As with the oceans, the Earth's atmosphere is subject to waves and tidal forces.
[src:magnetic-core/air] These are triggered by non-uniform heating by the Sun, and by the daily solar cycle, respectively.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Wave-like behavior can occur on a variety of scales, from smaller gravity waves that transfer momentum into the higher atmospheric layers, to much larger planetary waves, or Rossby waves.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Atmospheric tides are periodic oscillations of the troposphere and stratosphere that transport energy to the upper atmosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The first atmosphere, during the Early Earth's Hadean eon, consisted of gases in the solar nebula, primarily hydrogen, and probably simple hydrides such as those now found in the gas giants (Jupiter and Saturn), notably water vapor, methane and ammonia.
[src:magnetic-core/air] During this earliest era, the Moon-forming collision and numerous impacts with large meteorites heated the atmosphere, driving off the most volatile gases.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The collision with Theia, in particular, melted and ejected large portions of Earth's mantle and crust and outgassed significant amounts of steam which eventually cooled and condensed to contribute to ocean water at the end of the Hadean.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The increasing solidification of Earth's crust at the end of the Hadean closed off most of the advective heat transfer to the surface, causing the atmosphere to cool, which condensed most of the water vapor out of the air precipitating into a superocean.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Further outgassing from volcanism, supplemented by gases introduced by huge asteroids during the Late Heavy Bombardment, created the subsequent Archean atmosphere, which consisted largely of nitrogen plus carbon dioxide, methane and inert gases.
[src:magnetic-core/air] A major part of carbon dioxide emissions dissolved in water and reacted with metals such as calcium and magnesium during weathering of crustal rocks to form carbonates that were deposited as sediments.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Water-related sediments have been found that date from as early as 3.8 billion years ago.
[src:magnetic-core/air] About 3.4 billion years ago, nitrogen formed the major component of the then-stable "second atmosphere".
[src:magnetic-core/air] The influence of the evolution of life has to be taken into account rather soon in the history of the atmosphere because hints of earliest life forms appeared as early as 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:magnetic-core/air] How Earth at that time maintained a climate warm enough for liquid water and life, if the early Sun put out 30% lower solar radiance than today, is a puzzle known as the "faint young Sun paradox".
[src:magnetic-core/air] The geological record however shows a continuous relatively warm surface during the complete early temperature record of Earth – with the exception of one cold glacial phase about 2.4 billion years ago.
[src:magnetic-core/air] In the late Neoarchean, an oxygen-containing atmosphere began to develop, apparently due to a billion years of cyanobacterial photosynthesis (known as the Great Oxygenation Event), which have been found as stromatolite fossils from 2.7 billion years ago.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The early basic carbon isotopy (isotope ratio proportions) strongly suggests conditions similar to the current, and that the fundamental features of the carbon cycle became established as early as 4 billion years ago.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Ancient sediments in the Gabon dating from between about 2.15 and 2.08 billion years ago provide a record of Earth's dynamic oxygenation evolution.
[src:magnetic-core/air] These fluctuations in oxygenation were likely driven by the Lomagundi-Jatuli Carbon Isotope Excursion.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The constant re-arrangement of continents by plate tectonics influences the long-term evolution of the atmosphere by transferring carbon dioxide to and from large continental carbonate stores.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Before this time, any oxygen produced by cyanobacterial photosynthesis would be readily removed by the oxidation of reducing substances on the Earth's surface, notably ferrous iron, sulfur and atmospheric methane.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Free oxygen molecules did not start to accumulate in the atmosphere until the rate of production of oxygen began to exceed the availability of reductant materials that removed oxygen.
[src:magnetic-core/air] This point signifies a shift from a reducing atmosphere to an oxidizing atmosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] O2 showed major variations during the Proterozoic, including a billion-year period of euxinia, until reaching a steady state of more than 15% by the end of the Precambrian.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The amount of oxygen in the atmosphere has fluctuated over the last 600 million years, reaching a peak of about 35% around 280 million years ago during the Carboniferous period, significantly higher than today's 21%.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Two main processes govern changes in the atmosphere: the evolution of plants and their increasing role in carbon fixation, and the consumption of oxygen by rapidly diversifying animal faunae and also by plants for photorespiration and their own metabolic needs at night.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Breakdown of pyrite and volcanic eruptions release sulfur into the atmosphere, which reacts and hence reduces oxygen in the atmosphere.
[src:magnetic-core/air] However, volcanic eruptions also release carbon dioxide, which can fuel oxygenic photosynthesis by terrestrial and aquatic plants.
[src:magnetic-core/air] The cause of the variation of the amount of oxygen in the atmosphere is not precisely understood.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Periods with more oxygen in the atmosphere were often associated with more rapid development of animals.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Since 1750, human activity, especially after the Industrial Revolution, has increased the concentrations of various greenhouse gases, most importantly carbon dioxide, methane and nitrous oxide.
[src:magnetic-core/air] Greenhouse gas emissions, coupled with deforestation and destruction of wetlands via logging and land developments, have caused an observed rise in global temperatures, with the global average surface temperatures being 1.1 °C higher in the 2011–2020 decade than they were in 1850.
[src:magnetic-core/air] It has raised concerns of man-made climate change, which can have significant environmental impacts such as sea level rise, ocean acidification, glacial retreat (which threatens water security), increasing extreme weather events and wildfires, ecological collapse and mass dying of wildlife.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] At atmospheric pressure, three allotropic forms of iron exist, depending on temperature: alpha iron (α-Fe, ferrite), gamma iron (γ-Fe, austenite), and delta iron (δ-Fe, similar to alpha iron).
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] At very high pressure, a fourth form exists, epsilon iron (ε-Fe, hexaferrum).
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] Some controversial experimental evidence suggests the existence of a fifth form that is stable at very high pressures and temperatures.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] The phases of iron at atmospheric pressure are important because of the differences in solubility of carbon, forming different types of steel.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] The high-pressure phases of iron are important as models for the solid parts of planetary cores.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] The inner core of the Earth is generally assumed to consist essentially of a crystalline iron-nickel alloy with ε structure.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] The outer core surrounding the solid inner core is believed to be composed of liquid iron mixed with nickel and trace amounts of lighter elements.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] Below 912 °C (1,674 °F), iron has a body-centered cubic (bcc) crystal structure and is known as α-iron or **ferrite**.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] It is thermodynamically stable and a fairly soft metal. α-Fe can be subjected to pressures up to ca.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] 15 GPa before transforming into a high-pressure form termed ε-Fe, discussed below.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] Magnetically, α-iron is paramagnetic at high temperatures.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] However, below its Curie temperature (*T*C or *A2*) of 771 °C (1044K or 1420 °F), it becomes ferromagnetic.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] In the past, the paramagnetic form of α-iron was known as *beta iron* (β-Fe).
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] Even though the slight tetragonal distortion in the ferromagnetic state does constitute a true phase transition, the continuous nature of this transition results in only minor importance in steel heat treating.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] The A2 line forms the boundary between the beta iron and alpha fields in the phase diagram in Figure 1.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] Similarly, the A2 boundary is of only minor importance compared to the A1 (eutectoid), A3 and Acm critical temperatures.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] The Acm, where austenite is in equilibrium with cementite + γ-Fe, is beyond the right edge in Fig.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] The α + γ phase field is, technically, the β + γ field above the A2.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] The beta designation maintains continuity of the Greek-letter progression of phases in iron and steel: α-Fe, β-Fe, austenite (γ-Fe), high-temperature δ-Fe, and high-pressure hexaferrum (ε-Fe).
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] The primary phase of low-carbon or mild steel and most cast irons at room temperature is ferromagnetic α-Fe.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] It has a hardness of approximately 80 Brinell.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] When it dissolves in iron, carbon atoms occupy interstitial "holes".
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] Being about twice the diameter of the tetrahedral hole, the carbon introduces a strong local strain field.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] Mild steel (carbon steel with up to about 0.2 wt% C) consists mostly of α-Fe and increasing amounts of cementite (Fe3C, an iron carbide).
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] The mixture adopts a lamellar structure called pearlite.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] Since bainite and pearlite each contain α-Fe as a component, any iron-carbon alloy will contain some amount of α-Fe if it is allowed to reach equilibrium at room temperature.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] The amount of α-Fe depends on the cooling process.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] β-Fe and the A2 critical temperature are important in induction heating of steel, such as for surface-hardening heat treatments.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] Steel is typically austenitized at 900–1000 °C before it is quenched and tempered.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] The high-frequency alternating magnetic field of induction heating heats the steel by two mechanisms below the Curie temperature: resistance or Joule heating and ferromagnetic hysteresis losses.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] Above the A2 boundary, the hysteresis mechanism disappears and the required amount of energy per degree of temperature increase is thus substantially larger than below A2.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] Load-matching circuits may be needed to vary the impedance in the induction power source to compensate for the change.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] When heating iron above 912 °C (1,674 °F), its crystal structure changes to a face-centered cubic (fcc) crystalline structure.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] In this form it is called gamma iron (γ-Fe) or austenite. γ-iron can dissolve considerably more carbon (as much as 2.04% by mass at 1,146 °C).
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] This γ form of carbon saturation is exhibited in austenitic stainless steel.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] Peculiarly, above 1,394 °C (2,541 °F), iron changes back into the bcc structure, known as δ-Fe. δ-iron can dissolve as much as 0.08% of carbon by mass at 1,475 °C.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] It is stable up to its melting point of 1,538 °C (2,800 °F). δ-Fe cannot exist above 5.2 GPa, with austenite instead transitioning directly to a molten phase at these high pressures.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] The triple point of hexaferrum, ferrite, and austenite is 10.5 GPa at 750 K.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] Antiferromagnetism in alloys of epsilon-Fe with Mn, Os and Ru has been observed.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] An alternate stable form, if it exists, may appear at pressures of at least 50 GPa and temperatures of at least 1,500 K; it has been thought to have an orthorhombic or a double hcp structure.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] As of December 2011, recent and ongoing experiments are being conducted on high-pressure and superdense carbon allotropes.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] The melting point of iron is experimentally well defined for pressures less than 50 GPa.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] For greater pressures, published data (as of 2007) put the γ-ε-liquid triple point at pressures that differ by tens of gigapascals and 1000 K in the melting point.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] Generally speaking, molecular dynamics computer simulations of iron melting and shock wave experiments suggest higher melting points and a much steeper slope of the melting curve than static experiments carried out in diamond anvil cells.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] This same trend appears for ruthenium but not osmium.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] The exact temperatures at which iron will transition from one crystal structure to another depends on how much and what type of other elements are dissolved in the iron.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] The phase boundary between the different solid phases is drawn on a binary phase diagram, usually plotted as temperature versus percent iron.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] Adding some elements, such as Chromium, narrows the temperature range for the gamma phase, while others increase the temperature range of the gamma phase.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] In elements that reduce the gamma phase range, the alpha-gamma phase boundary connects with the gamma-delta phase boundary, forming what is usually called the *Gamma loop*.
[src:magnetic-core/allotropes-of-iron] Adding Gamma loop additives keeps the iron in a body-centered cubic structure and prevents the steel from suffering phase transition to other solid states.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:magnetic-core/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] An **alternator** (or **synchronous generator**) is an electrical generator that converts mechanical energy to electrical energy in the form of alternating current (AC).
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] For reasons of cost and simplicity, most alternators use a rotating magnetic field with a stationary armature.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The rotor coil is externally excited by a small direct current (DC), while the AC is generated in the stationary coils.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Occasionally, a linear alternator or a rotating armature with a stationary magnetic field is used.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Although any AC electrical generator might be called an alternator, usually the term refers to small rotating machines driven by automotive and other internal combustion engines.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The term usually applies those types with externally excited rotor coils.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] An alternator that uses a permanent magnet for its magnetic field is called a magneto.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Alternators in power stations driven by steam turbines are called turbo-alternators.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Large 50 or 60 Hz three-phase alternators in power plants generate most of the world's electric power, which is distributed by electric power grids.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Alternating current generating systems were known in simple forms from the discovery of the magnetic induction of electric current in the 1830s.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Rotating generators naturally produced alternating current, but since there was little use for it, it was normally converted into direct current via the addition of a commutator in the generator.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The early machines were developed by pioneers such as Michael Faraday and Hippolyte Pixii.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Faraday developed the "rotating rectangle", whose operation was *heteropolar* – each active conductor passed successively through regions where the magnetic field was in opposite directions.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Lord Kelvin and Sebastian Ferranti also developed early alternators, producing frequencies between 100 and 300 Hz.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The late 1870s saw the introduction of the first large-scale electrical systems with central generation stations to power Arc lamps, used to light whole streets, factory yards, or the interior of large warehouses.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Some, such as Yablochkov arc lamps introduced in 1878, ran better on alternating current, and the development of these early AC generating systems was accompanied by the first use of the word "alternator".
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Supplying the proper amount of voltage from generating stations in these early systems was left up to the engineer's skill in "riding the load".
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] In 1883 the Ganz Works invented the constant voltage generator that could produce a stated output voltage, regardless of the value of the actual load.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The introduction of transformers in the mid-1880s led to the widespread use of alternating current and the use of alternators needed to produce it.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] After 1891, polyphase alternators were introduced to supply currents of multiple differing phases.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Later alternators were designed for various alternating current frequencies between sixteen and about one hundred hertz for use with arc lighting, incandescent lighting, and electric motors.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Specialized radio frequency alternators like the Alexanderson alternator were developed as longwave radio transmitters around World War 1 and used in a few high power wireless telegraphy stations before vacuum tube transmitters replaced them.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] A conductor moving relative to a magnetic field develops an electromotive force (EMF) in it (Faraday's Law).
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] This EMF reverses its polarity when it moves under magnetic poles of opposite polarity.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Typically, a rotating magnet, called the rotor, turns within a stationary set of conductors, called the stator, wound in coils on an iron core.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The field cuts across the conductors, generating an induced EMF (electromotive force), as the mechanical input causes the rotor to turn.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The rotating magnetic field induces an AC voltage in the stator windings.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Since the currents in the stator windings vary in step with the position of the rotor, an alternator is a synchronous generator.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The rotor's magnetic field may be produced by permanent magnets or by a field coil electromagnet.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Automotive alternators use a rotor winding, which allows control of the alternator's generated voltage by varying the current in the rotor field winding.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Permanent magnet machines avoid the loss due to magnetizing current in the rotor, but are restricted in size due to the cost of the magnet material.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Since the permanent magnet field is constant, the terminal voltage varies directly with the speed of the generator.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Brushless AC generators are usually larger than those used in automotive applications.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] An automatic voltage control device controls the field current to keep the output voltage constant.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] If the output voltage from the stationary armature coils drops due to an increase in demand, more current is fed into the rotating field coils through the voltage regulator (VR).
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] This increases the magnetic field around the field coils, which induces a greater voltage in the armature coils.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Thus, the output voltage is brought back up to its original value.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Alternators used in central power stations also control the field current to regulate reactive power and to help stabilize the power system against the effects of momentary faults.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Often, there are three sets of stator windings, physically offset so that the rotating magnetic field produces a three-phase current, displaced by one-third of a period with respect to each other.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] One cycle of alternating current is produced each time a pair of field poles passes over a point on the stationary winding.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The relation between speed and frequency is $N=120f/P$ , where f is the frequency in Hz (cycles per second).
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] P is the number of poles (2, 4, 6, ...), and N is the rotational speed in revolutions per minute (r/min).
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Old descriptions of alternating current systems sometimes give the frequency in terms of alternations per minute, counting each half-cycle as one *alternation*; so 12,000 alternations per minute corresponds to 100 Hz.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] An alternator's output frequency depends on the number of poles and the rotational speed.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The speed corresponding to a particular frequency is called the *synchronous speed*.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Alternators may be classified by the method of excitation, number of phases, the type of rotation, cooling method, and their application.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] There are two main ways to produce the magnetic field used in the alternators: by using permanent magnets, which create their persistent magnetic field, or by using field coils.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The alternators that use permanent magnets are specifically called magnetos.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] In other alternators, wound field coils form an electromagnet to produce the rotating magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] A device that uses permanent magnets to produce alternating current is called a permanent magnet alternator (PMA).
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] A permanent magnet generator (PMG) may produce either alternating current or direct current if it has a commutator.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] This method of excitation consists of a smaller direct-current (DC) generator fixed on the same shaft as the alternator.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The DC generator generates a small amount of electricity, just enough to *excite* the field coils of the connected alternator to generate electricity.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] A variation of this system is a type of alternator that uses direct current from a battery for initial excitation upon start-up, after which the alternator becomes self-excited.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] This method of excitation consists of a smaller alternating-current (AC) generator fixed on the same shaft as the alternator.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The AC stator generates a small amount of field coil excitation current, which is induced in the rotor and rectified to DC by a bridge rectifier built in to the windings where it excites the field coils of the larger connected alternator to generate electricity.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] This system has the advantage of not requiring brushes, which increases service life, although with a slightly lower overall efficiency.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] This method depends on residual magnetism retained in the iron core to generate a weak magnetic field, which would allow a weak voltage to be generated.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] This voltage is used to excite the field coils so the alternator can generate stronger voltage as part of its *build up* process.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] After the initial AC voltage buildup, the field is supplied with rectified voltage from the alternator.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] A brushless alternator is composed of two alternators built end-to-end on one shaft.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Until 1966, alternators used brushes with rotating field.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] With the advancement in semiconductor technology, brushless alternators are possible.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Smaller brushless alternators may look like one unit, but the two parts are readily identifiable in the large versions.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The main alternator is the larger of the two sections, and the smaller one is the exciter.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The exciter has stationary field coils and a rotating armature (power coils).
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The main alternator uses the opposite configuration with a rotating field and stationary armature.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] A bridge rectifier, called the rotating rectifier assembly, is mounted on the rotor.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Neither brushes nor slip rings are used, which reduces the number of wearing parts.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The main alternator has a rotating field and a stationary armature (power generation windings).
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Varying the amount of current through the stationary exciter field coils varies the 3-phase output from the exciter.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] This output is rectified by a rotating rectifier assembly mounted on the rotor, and the resultant DC supplies the rotating field of the main alternator and hence alternator output.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The result is that a small DC exciter current indirectly controls the output of the main alternator.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Another way to classify alternators is by the number of phases of their output voltage.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The output can be single-phase or polyphase.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Three-phase alternators are the most common, but polyphase alternators can be two-phase, six-phase, or more.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The revolving part of alternators can be the armature or the magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The revolving armature type has the armature wound on the rotor, where the winding moves through a stationary magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The revolving armature type is not often used.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The revolving field type has a magnetic field on the rotor to rotate through a stationary armature winding.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The stationary armature can be wound for any convenient medium voltage level, up to tens of thousands of volts; manufacture of slip ring connections for more than a few thousand volts is costly and inconvenient.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Many alternators are cooled by ambient air, forced through the enclosure by an attached fan on the shaft that drives the alternator.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] In vehicles such as transit buses, a heavy demand on the electrical system may require a large alternator to be oil-cooled.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] In marine applications water-cooling is also used.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Expensive automobiles may use water-cooled alternators to meet high electrical system demands.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Most power generation stations use synchronous machines as their generators.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The connection of these generators to the utility grid requires synchronization conditions to be met.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Synchronous generators provide several important system services.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Their inherent rotational inertia slows the initial frequency decline after a sudden loss of generation, allowing turbine governors and other frequency-control reserves time to respond and restore balance.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] This role is increasingly significant as the share of non-synchronous generation, such as solar photovoltaics and many modern wind plants, grows in many power systems.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Alternators are used in modern internal combustion engine automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] With the availability of affordable silicon-diode rectifiers, alternators were used instead.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] In later diesel–electric locomotives and diesel–electric multiple units, the prime mover turns an alternator which provides electricity for the traction motors (AC or DC).
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The traction alternator usually incorporates integral silicon diode rectifiers to provide the traction motors with up to 1,200 volts DC.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The first diesel electric locomotives, and many of those still in service, use DC generators as, before silicon power electronics, it was easier to control the speed of DC traction motors.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Most of these had two generators: one to generate the excitation current for a larger main generator.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Optionally, the generator also supplies head-end power (HEP) or power for electric train heating.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] The HEP option requires a constant engine speed, typically 900 r/min for a 480 V 60 Hz HEP application, even when the locomotive is not moving.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Marine alternators used in yachts are similar to automotive alternators, with appropriate adaptations to the salt-water environment.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Marine alternators are designed to be explosion proof (ignition protected) so that brush sparking will not ignite explosive gas mixtures in an engine room environment.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Depending on the type of system installed, they may be 12 or 24 volts.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Larger marine diesels may have two or more alternators to cope with the heavy electrical demand of a modern yacht.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] On single alternator circuits, the power may be split between the engine starting battery and the domestic or house battery (or batteries) by use of a split-charge diode (battery isolator) or a voltage-sensitive relay.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Due to the high cost of large house battery banks, Marine alternators generally use external regulators.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Multistep regulators control the field current to maximize the charging effectiveness (time to charge) and battery life.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Multistep regulators can be programmed for different battery types.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Two temperature sensors can be added: one for the battery to adjust the charging voltage and an over-temperature sensor on the actual alternator to protect it from overheating.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] High-frequency alternators of the variable-reluctance type were applied commercially to radio transmission in low-frequency radio bands.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] These were used for transmitting Morse code and, experimentally, for transmitting voice and music.
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] In the Alexanderson alternator, both the field winding and armature winding are stationary, and current is induced in the armature by the changing magnetic reluctance of the rotor (which has no windings or current-carrying parts).
[src:magnetic-core/alternator] Such machines were made to produce radio frequency current for radio transmissions, although the efficiency was low.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] An **amorphous metal** (also known as **metallic glass**, **glassy metal**, or **shiny metal**) is a solid metallic material, usually an alloy, with disordered atomic-scale structure.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Most metals are crystalline in their solid state, which means they have a highly ordered arrangement of atoms.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Amorphous metals are non-crystalline, and have a glass-like structure.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] But unlike common glasses, such as window glass, which are typically electrical insulators, amorphous metals have good electrical conductivity and can show metallic luster.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Amorphous metals can be produced in several ways, including extremely rapid cooling, physical vapor deposition, solid-state reaction, ion irradiation, and mechanical alloying.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Small batches of amorphous metals have been produced through a variety of quick-cooling methods, such as amorphous metal ribbons produced by sputtering molten metal onto a spinning metal disk (melt spinning).
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The rapid cooling (millions of degrees Celsius per second) comes too fast for crystals to form and the material is "locked" in a glassy state.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Alloys with cooling rates low enough to allow formation of amorphous structure in thick layers (i.e., over 1 millimetre or 0.039 inches) have been produced and are known as *bulk metallic glasses*.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Batches of amorphous steel with three times the strength of conventional steel alloys have been produced.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] New techniques such as 3D printing, also characterised by high cooling rates, are an active research topic.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The first reported metallic glass was Au75Si25, produced at Caltech by Klement, Willens, and Duwez in 1960.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] This and other early glass-forming alloys had to be rapidly cooled (on the order of one megakelvin per second, 106 K/s) to avoid crystallization.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] An important consequence of this was that metallic glasses could be produced in a few forms (typically ribbons, foils, or wires) in which one dimension was small so that heat could be extracted quickly enough to achieve the required cooling rate.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] As a result, metallic glass specimens (with a few exceptions) were limited to thicknesses of less than one hundred microns.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] In 1969, an alloy of 77.5% palladium, 6% copper, and 16.5% silicon was found to have critical cooling rate between 100 and 1000 K/s.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] In 1976, Liebermann and Graham developed a method of manufacturing thin ribbons of amorphous metal on a supercooled fast-spinning wheel.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] This was an alloy of iron, nickel, and boron.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The material, known as *Metglas*, was commercialized in the early 1980s and became used for low-loss power distribution transformers (amorphous metal transformer).
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Metglas-2605 is composed of 80% iron and 20% boron, has a Curie temperature of 646 K (373 °C; 703 °F) and a room temperature saturation magnetization of 1.56 teslas.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] In the early 1980s, glassy ingots with a diameter of 5 mm (0.20 in) were produced with an alloy of 55% palladium, 22.5% lead, and 22.5% antimony, by surface etching followed with heating-cooling cycles.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Using boron oxide flux, the achievable thickness increased to one centimeter.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] In 1982, a study on amorphous metal structural relaxation indicated a relationship between the specific heat and temperature of (Fe0.5Ni0.5)83P17.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] As the material was heated, the two properties displayed a negative relationship starting at 375 K, due to the change in relaxed amorphous states.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] When the material was annealed for periods from 1 to 48 hours, the properties instead displayed a positive relationship starting at 475 K for all annealing periods, since the annealing induced structure disappears at that temperature.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] In this study, amorphous alloys demonstrated glass transition and a super cooled liquid region.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Between 1988 and 1992, more studies found more glass-type alloys with glass transition and a super cooled liquid region.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] From those studies, bulk glass alloys were made of La, Mg, and Zr, and these alloys demonstrated plasticity even with ribbon thickness from 20 μm to 50 μm.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The plasticity was a stark difference to past amorphous metals that became brittle at those thicknesses.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] In 1988, alloys of lanthanum, aluminium, and copper ore were revealed to be glass-forming.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Al-based metallic glasses containing scandium exhibited a record-type tensile mechanical strength of about 1,500 MPa (220 ksi).
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Bulk amorphous alloys of several millimeters in thickness were rare, although Pd-based amorphous alloys had been formed into rods with a 2 mm (0.079 in) diameter by quenching, and spheres with a 10 mm (0.39 in) diameter were formed by repetition flux melting with B2O3 and quenching.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] New techniques were found in 1990, producing alloys that form glasses at cooling rates as low as one kelvin per second.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] These cooling rates can be achieved by simple casting into metallic molds.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] These alloys can be cast into parts several centimeters thick while retaining an amorphous structure.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The best glass-forming alloys were based on zirconium and palladium, but alloys based on iron, titanium, copper, magnesium, and other metals are known.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The process exploited a phenomenon called "confusion".
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Such alloys contain many elements (often four or more) such that upon cooling sufficiently quickly, constituent atoms cannot achieve an equilibrium crystalline state before their mobility is lost.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] In this way, the random disordered state of the atoms is "locked in".
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] In 1992, the commercial amorphous alloy, Vitreloy 1 (41.2% Zr, 13.8% Ti, 12.5% Cu, 10% Ni, and 22.5% Be), was developed at Caltech, as a part of Department of Energy and NASA research of new aerospace materials.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] By 2000, research in Tohoku University and Caltech yielded multicomponent alloys based on lanthanum, magnesium, zirconium, palladium, iron, copper, and titanium, with critical cooling rate between 1 K/s and 100 K/s, comparable to oxide glasses.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] In 2004, bulk amorphous steel was successfully produced by a groups at Oak Ridge National Laboratory, which refers to their product as "glassy steel", and another at University of Virginia, named "DARVA-Glass 101".
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The product is non-magnetic at room temperature and significantly stronger than conventional steel.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] In 2018, a team at SLAC National Accelerator Laboratory, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) and Northwestern University reported the use of artificial intelligence to predict and evaluate samples of 20,000 different likely metallic glass alloys in a year.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Amorphous metal is usually an alloy rather than a pure metal.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The alloys contain atoms of significantly different sizes, leading to low free volume (and therefore up to orders of magnitude higher viscosity than other metals and alloys) in molten state.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The viscosity prevents the atoms from moving enough to form an ordered lattice.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The material displays low shrinkage during cooling, and resistance to plastic deformation.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The absence of grain boundaries, the weak spots of crystalline materials, leads to better wear resistance and less corrosion.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Amorphous metals, while technically glasses, are much tougher and less brittle than oxide glasses and ceramics.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Amorphous metals are either non-ferromagnetic, if they are composed of Ln, Mg, Zr, Ti, Pd, Ca, Cu, Pt and Au, or ferromagnetic, if they are composed of Fe, Co, and Ni.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Thermal conductivity is lower than in crystalline metals.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] As formation of amorphous structure relies on fast cooling, this limits the thickness of amorphous structures.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] To form amorphous structure despite slower cooling, the alloy has to be made of three or more components, leading to complex crystal units with higher potential energy and lower odds of formation.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The atomic radius of the components has to be significantly different (over 12%), to achieve high packing density and low free volume.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The combination of components should have negative mixing heat, inhibiting crystal nucleation and prolonging the time the molten metal stays in supercooled state.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] As temperatures change, the electrical resistivity of amorphous metals behaves very different than that of regular metals.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] While resistivity in crystalline metals generally increases with temperature, following Matthiessen's rule, resistivity in many amorphous metals decreases with increasing temperature.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] This effect can be observed in amorphous metals of high resistivities between 150 and 300 microohm-centimeters.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] In these metals, the scattering events causing the resistivity of the metal are not statistically independent, thus explaining the breakdown of Matthiessen's rule.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The fact that the thermal change of the resistivity in amorphous metals can be negative over a large range of temperatures and correlated to their absolute resistivity values was identified by Mooij in 1973, becoming Mooijs-rule.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Alloys of boron, silicon, phosphorus, and other glass formers with magnetic metals (iron, cobalt, nickel) have high magnetic susceptibility, with low coercivity and high electrical resistance.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Usually the electrical conductivity of a metallic glass is of the same low order of magnitude as of a molten metal just above the melting point.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The high resistance leads to low losses by eddy currents when subjected to alternating magnetic fields, a property useful for e.g. transformer magnetic cores.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Their low coercivity also contributes to low loss.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Buckel and Hilsch discovered the superconductivity of amorphous metal thin films experimentally in the early 1950s.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] For certain metallic elements the superconducting critical temperature *T*c can be higher in the amorphous state (e.g. upon alloying) than in the crystalline state, and in several cases *T*c increases upon increasing the structural disorder.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] This behavior can be explained by the effect of structural disorder on electron-phonon coupling.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Amorphous metals have higher tensile yield strengths and higher elastic strain limits than polycrystalline metal alloys, but their ductilities and fatigue strengths are lower.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Amorphous alloys have a variety of potentially useful properties.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] In particular, they tend to be stronger than crystalline alloys of similar chemical composition, and they can sustain larger reversible ("elastic") deformations than crystalline alloys.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Amorphous metals derive their strength directly from their non-crystalline structure, which does not have defects (such as dislocations) that limit their strength.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Vitreloy is an amorphous metal with a tensile strength almost double that of high-grade titanium.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] However, metallic glasses at room temperature are not ductile and tend to fail suddenly and surprisingly when loaded in tension, which limits applicability in reliability-critical applications.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Metal matrix composites consisting of a ductile crystalline metal matrix containing dendritic particles or fibers of an amorphous glass metal are an alternative.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Perhaps the most useful property of bulk amorphous alloys is that they are true glasses, which means that they soften and flow upon heating.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] This allows for easy processing, such as by injection molding, in much the same way as polymers.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] As a result, amorphous alloys have been commercialized for use in sports equipment, medical devices, and as cases for electronic equipment.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Thin films of amorphous metals can be deposited as protective coatings via high velocity oxygen fuel.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The most important application exploits the magnetic properties of some ferromagnetic metallic glasses.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The low magnetization loss is used in high efficiency transformers at line frequency and in some higher frequency transformers.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Amorphous steel is very brittle that makes it difficult to punch into motor laminations.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Electronic article surveillance (such as passive ID tags) often uses metallic glasses because of these magnetic properties.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Ti-based metallic glass, when made into thin pipes, have a high tensile strength of 2,100 MPa (300 ksi), elastic elongation of 2% and high corrosion resistance.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] A Ti–Zr–Cu–Ni–Sn metallic glass was used to improve the sensitivity of a Coriolis flow meter.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] This flow meter is about 28-53 times more sensitive than conventional meters, which can be applied in fossil-fuel, chemical, environmental, semiconductor and medical science industries.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Zr-Al-Ni-Cu based metallic glass can be shaped into 2.2 to 5 by 4 mm (0.087 to 0.197 by 0.157 in) pressure sensors for automobile and other industries.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Such sensors are smaller, more sensitive, and possess greater pressure endurance than conventional stainless steel.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Additionally, this alloy was used to make the world's smallest geared motor with diameter 1.5 and 9.9 mm (0.059 and 0.390 in) at the time.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Amorphous metals exhibit unique softening behavior above their glass transition and this softening has been increasingly explored for thermoplastic forming of metallic glasses.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Such low softening temperature supports simple methods for making nanoparticle composites (e.g. carbon nanotubes) and bulk metallic glasses.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Metallic glasses can be patterned on scales as small as 10 nm.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] This may solve problems of nanoimprint lithography where silicon nano-molds are expensive and break easily.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Nano-molds made from metallic glasses are easy to fabricate and more durable.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The superior electronic, thermal and mechanical properties of bulk metallic glasses compared to polymers make them a good candidate for nanocomposites for electronic applications such as field electron emission devices.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Ti40Cu36Pd14Zr10 is claimed to be noncarcinogenic, about three times stronger than titanium, with an elastic modulus that nearly matches bones.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] It has high wear resistance and does not produce abrasion powder.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The alloy does not undergo shrinkage on solidification.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] A surface structure can be generated that is biologically attachable by surface modification using laser pulses, allowing better joining with bone for applications such as joint replacement.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Laser powder bed fusion (LPBF) has been used to process Zr-based bulk metallic glass (BMG) for biomedical applications.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Zr-based BMGs shows good biocompatibility, supporting osteoblastic cell growth similar to Ti-6Al-4V.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The favorable response coupled with the ability to tailor surface properties through SLM highlights the promise of SLM Zr- based BMGs like AMLOY-ZR01 for orthopaedic implant applications.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] However, their degradation under inflammatory conditions requires further investigation.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Mg60Zn35Ca5 is under investigation as a biomaterial for implantation into bones as screws, pins, or plates, and to fix fractures.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Unlike traditional steel or titanium, this material is a bioabsorbable metallic glass: it dissolves in organisms at a rate of roughly 1 millimeter per month and is replaced with bone tissue.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] This speed can be adjusted by varying the zinc content.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] SAM2X5-630 is claimed to have the highest recorded plasticity of any steel alloy, essentially the highest threshold at which a material can withstand an impact without deforming permanently.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The alloy can withstand pressure up to 12.5 GPa (123,000 atm) without permanent deformation.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] This is the highest impact resistance of any bulk metallic glass as of 2016.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] This makes it as an attractive option for armour material and other applications that require high stress tolerance.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Amorphous iron-based alloys can reduce hysteresis losses in electric motors by 75–90% under typical operating conditions (50–400 Hz).
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Avoiding grain boundaries and magnetocrystalline anisotropy avoids "pinning" domain walls, allowing high coercivity (typically 30–100 A/m).
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] One challenge when synthesising a metallic glass is that the required fast cooling rates often translate to very small samples.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] 3D-printing or additive manufacturing has been suggested and proven as a method to create larger bulk samples.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Selective laser melting (SLM) is one example of an additive manufacturing method that has been used to make iron based metallic glasses and zirconia based bulk metallic glasses.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Laser foil printing (LFP) is another method where foils of the amorphous metals are stacked and welded together, layer by layer.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Modelling of the manufacturing process is under study to reduce traditional time and resource consuming trial and error.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Bulk metallic glasses have been modeled using atomic scale simulations (within the density functional theory framework) in a similar manner to high entropy alloys.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] This has allowed predictions to be made about their behavior, stability and many more properties.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] As such, new bulk metallic glass systems can be tested and tailored for a specific purpose (e.g. bone replacement or aero-engine component) without as much empirical searching of the phase space or experimental trial and error.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Ab-initio molecular dynamics (MD) simulation confirmed that the atomic surface structure of a Ni-Nb metallic glass observed by scanning tunneling microscopy is a kind of spectroscopy.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] At negative applied bias it visualizes only one sort of atoms (Ni) owing to the structure of electronic density of states calculated using ab-initio MD simulation.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] One common way to try and understand the electronic properties of amorphous metals is by comparing them to liquid metals, which are similarly disordered, and for which established theoretical frameworks exist.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] For simple amorphous metals, good estimations can be reached by semi-classical modelling of the movement of individual electrons using the Boltzmann equation and approximating the scattering potential as the superposition of the electronic potential of each nucleus in the surrounding metal.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] To simplify the calculations, the electronic potentials of the atomic nuclei can be truncated to give a muffin-tin pseudopotential.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] In this theory, there are two main effects that govern the change of resistivity with increasing temperatures.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Both are based on the induction of vibrations of the atomic nuclei of the metal as temperatures increase.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] One is, that the atomic structure gets increasingly smeared out as the exact positions of the atomic nuclei get less and less well defined.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] The other is the introduction of phonons.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] While the smearing out generally decreases the resistivity of the metal, the introduction of phonons generally adds scattering sites and therefore increases resistivity.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Together, they can explain the anomalous decrease of resistivity in amorphous metals, as the first part outweighs the second.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] In contrast to regular crystalline metals, the phonon contribution in an amorphous metal does not get frozen out at low temperatures.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] Due to the lack of a defined crystal structure, there are always some phonon wavelengths that can be excited.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] While this semi-classical approach holds well for many amorphous metals, it generally breaks down under more extreme conditions.
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] At very low temperatures, the quantum nature of the electrons leads to long range interference effects of the electrons with each other in what is called "weak localization effects".
[src:magnetic-core/amorphous-metal] In very strongly disordered metals, impurities in the atomic structure can induce bound electronic states in what is called "Anderson localization", effectively binding the electrons and inhibiting their movement.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] In classical electromagnetism, **Ampère's circuital law**, often simply called **Ampère's law**, and sometimes **Oersted's law**, relates the circulation of a magnetic field around a closed loop to the electric current passing through that loop.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] The law was inspired by Hans Christian Ørsted's 1820 discovery that an electric current generates a magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] This finding prompted theoretical and experimental work by André-Marie Ampère and others, eventually leading to the formulation of the law in its modern form.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] James Clerk Maxwell published the law in 1855.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] In 1865, he generalized the law to account for time-varying electric currents by introducing the displacement current term.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] The resulting equation, often called the **Ampère–Maxwell law**, is one of Maxwell's equations that form the foundation of classical electromagnetism.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] Until the early 19th century, electricity and magnetism were thought to be completely separate phenomena.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] This view changed in 1820 when Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted discovered that an electric current produces a magnetic effect.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] He observed that a compass needle placed near a current-carrying wire deflected so that it aligned perpendicular to the wire.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] In a series of experiments, Ørsted demonstrated that the current could influence magnetic poles nearby, and that its effect extended outward from the wire.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] He also observed that this magnetic influence formed a vortex around the wire.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] Ørsted's discovery sparked a great deal of research into the relation between electricity and magnetism.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] André-Marie Ampère investigated the magnetic force between two current-carrying wires, discovering Ampère's force law.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] In the 1850s, Scottish mathematical physicist James Clerk Maxwell generalized these results and others into a single mathematical law.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] The original form of Maxwell's circuital law, which he discussed in 1854 in correspondence with William Thomson (later ennobled as Lord Kelvin) and published in his 1855 paper "On Faraday's Lines of Force", was based on an analogy to hydrodynamics.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] The original circuital law relates magnetic fields to electric currents that produce them and can be used to determine either the magnetic field associated with a given current, or the current associated with a given magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] However, it applies only in magnetostatic situations, involving steady, continuous currents flowing in closed circuits.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] In systems where electric fields vary with time, the original law (as given in this section) must be modified by adding a term known as Maxwell's correction (see below).
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] The integral form of the original circuital law is a line integral of the magnetic field around some closed curve C (arbitrary but must be closed).
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] The curve C in turn bounds both a surface S which the electric current passes through (again arbitrary but not closed—since no three-dimensional volume is enclosed by S), and encloses the current.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] The mathematical statement of the law is a relation between the circulation of the magnetic field around some path (line integral) due to the current which passes through that enclosed path (surface integral).
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] In terms of total current, (which is the sum of both free current and bound current) the line integral of the magnetic **B**-field (in teslas, T) around closed curve C is proportional to the total current *I*enc passing through a surface S (enclosed by C).
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] In terms of free current, the line integral of the magnetic **H**-field (in amperes per metre, A·m−1) around closed curve C equals the free current *I*f,enc through a surface S.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] There are a number of ambiguities in the above definitions that require clarification and a choice of convention.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] Second, there are infinitely many possible surfaces S that have the curve C as their border.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] (Imagine a soap film on a wire loop, which can be deformed by blowing on the film).
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] Which of those surfaces is to be chosen?
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] If the loop does not lie in a single plane, for example, there is no one obvious choice.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] The answer is that it does not matter: in the magnetostatic case, the current density is solenoidal (see next section), so the divergence theorem and continuity equation imply that the flux through any surface with boundary C, with the same sign convention, is the same.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] In practice, one usually chooses the most convenient surface (with the given boundary) to integrate over.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] The electric current that arises in the simplest textbook situations would be classified as "free current"—for example, the current that passes through a wire or battery.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] In contrast, "bound current" arises in the context of bulk materials that can be magnetized and/or polarized.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] When a material is magnetized (for example, by placing it in an external magnetic field), the electrons remain bound to their respective atoms, but behave as if they were orbiting the nucleus in a particular direction, creating a microscopic current.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] When the currents from all these atoms are put together, they create the same effect as a macroscopic current, circulating perpetually around the magnetized object.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] This magnetization current **J**M is one contribution to "bound current".
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] The other source of bound current is bound charge.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] When an electric field is applied, the positive and negative bound charges can separate over atomic distances in polarizable materials, and when the bound charges move, the polarization changes, creating another contribution to the "bound current", the polarization current **J**P.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] with **J**f the "free" or "conduction" current density.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] All current is fundamentally the same, microscopically.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] Nevertheless, there are often practical reasons for wanting to treat bound current differently from free current.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] For example, the bound current usually originates over atomic dimensions, and one may wish to take advantage of a simpler theory intended for larger dimensions.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] The result is that the more microscopic Ampère's circuital law, expressed in terms of **B** and the microscopic current (which includes free, magnetization and polarization currents), is sometimes put into the equivalent form below in terms of **H** and the free current only.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] For a detailed definition of free current and bound current, and the proof that the two formulations are equivalent, see the "proof" section below.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] There are two important issues regarding the circuital law that require closer scrutiny.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] First, there is an issue regarding the continuity equation for electrical charge.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] In vector calculus, the identity for the divergence of a curl states that the divergence of the curl of a vector field must always be zero.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] Hence $\nabla \cdot (\nabla \times \mathbf {B} )=0\,,$ and so the original Ampère's circuital law implies that $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {J} =0\,,$ i.e. that the current density is solenoidal.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] But in general, reality follows the continuity equation for electric charge: $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {J} =-{\frac {\partial \rho }{\partial t}}\,,$ which is nonzero for a time-varying charge density.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] An example occurs in a capacitor circuit where time-varying charge densities exist on the plates.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] Second, there is an issue regarding the propagation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] To 'resolve' these situations (w/ eqn. above), the contribution of displacement current must be added to the current term in the circuital law.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] James Clerk Maxwell conceived of displacement current as a polarization current in the dielectric vortex sea, which he used to model the magnetic field hydrodynamically and mechanically.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] He added this displacement current to Ampère's circuital law at equation 112 in his 1861 paper "On Physical Lines of Force".
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] In free space, the displacement current is related to the time rate of change of electric field.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] In a dielectric the above contribution to displacement current is present too, but a major contribution to the displacement current is related to the polarization of the individual molecules of the dielectric material.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] Even though charges cannot flow freely in a dielectric, the charges in molecules can move a little under the influence of an electric field.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] The positive and negative charges in molecules separate under the applied field, causing an increase in the state of polarization, expressed as the polarization density **P**.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] A changing state of polarization is equivalent to a current.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] The first term on the right hand side is present everywhere, even in a vacuum.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] It doesn't involve any actual movement of charge, but it nevertheless has an associated magnetic field, as if it were an actual current.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] Some authors apply the name *displacement current* to only this contribution.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] The second term on the right hand side is the displacement current as originally conceived by Maxwell, associated with the polarization of the individual molecules of the dielectric material.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] Maxwell's original explanation for displacement current focused upon the situation that occurs in dielectric media.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] In the modern post-aether era, the concept has been extended to apply to situations with no material media present, for example, to the vacuum between the plates of a charging vacuum capacitor.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] For greater discussion see Displacement current.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] Next, the circuital equation is extended by including the polarization current, thereby remedying the limited applicability of the original circuital law.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] In both forms **J** includes magnetization current density as well as conduction and polarization current densities.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] Because ∇ ⋅ **D** = *ρ*, the charge continuity issue with Ampère's original formulation is no longer a problem.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] Because of the term in *ε*0⁠∂**E**/∂*t*⁠, wave propagation in free space now is possible.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] With the addition of the displacement current, Maxwell was able to hypothesize (correctly) that light was a form of electromagnetic wave.
[src:magnetic-core/ampere-s-circuital-law] See electromagnetic wave equation for a discussion of this important discovery.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] It is made of ferromagnetic metal such as iron, or ferrimagnetic compounds such as ferrites.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The high permeability, relative to the surrounding air, causes the magnetic field lines to be concentrated in the core material.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The magnetic field is often created by a current-carrying coil of wire around the core.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The use of a magnetic core can increase the strength of magnetic field in an electromagnetic coil by a factor of several hundred times what it would be without the core.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] However, magnetic cores have side effects which must be taken into account.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] In alternating current (AC) devices they cause energy losses, called core losses, due to hysteresis and eddy currents in applications such as transformers and inductors.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] "Soft" magnetic materials with low coercivity and hysteresis, such as silicon steel, or ferrite, are usually used in cores.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] An electric current through a wire wound into a coil creates a magnetic field through the center of the coil, due to Ampere's circuital law.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Coils are widely used in electronic components such as electromagnets, inductors, transformers, electric motors and generators.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] A coil without a magnetic core is called an "air core" coil.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Adding a piece of ferromagnetic or ferrimagnetic material in the center of the coil can increase the magnetic field by hundreds or thousands of times; this is called a magnetic core.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The field of the wire penetrates the core material, magnetizing it, so that the strong magnetic field of the core adds to the field created by the wire.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The amount that the magnetic field is increased by the core depends on the magnetic permeability of the core material.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Because side effects such as eddy currents and hysteresis can cause frequency-dependent energy losses, different core materials are used for coils used at different frequencies.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] In some cases the losses are undesirable and with very strong fields saturation can be a problem, and an 'air core' is used.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] A former may still be used; a piece of material, such as plastic or a composite, that may not have any significant magnetic permeability but which simply holds the coils of wires in place.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] "Soft" (annealed) iron is used in magnetic assemblies, direct current (DC) electromagnets and in some electric motors; and it can create a concentrated field that is as much as 50,000 times more intense than an air core.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The current flowing through the resistance of the metal heats it by Joule heating, causing significant power losses.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Therefore, solid iron cores are not used in transformers or inductors, they are replaced by laminated or powdered iron cores, or nonconductive cores like ferrite.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Laminated magnetic cores are made of stacks of thin iron sheets coated with an insulating layer, lying as much as possible parallel with the lines of flux.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The layers of insulation serve as a barrier to eddy currents, so eddy currents can only flow in narrow loops within the thickness of each single lamination.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Since the current in an eddy current loop is proportional to the area of the loop, this prevents most of the current from flowing, reducing eddy currents to a very small level.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Since power dissipated is proportional to the square of the current, breaking a large core into narrow laminations reduces the power losses drastically.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] From this, it can be seen that the thinner the laminations, the lower the eddy current losses.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] A small addition of silicon to iron (around 3%) results in a dramatic increase of the resistivity of the metal, up to four times higher.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The higher resistivity reduces the eddy currents, so silicon steel is used in transformer cores.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Further increase in silicon concentration impairs the steel's mechanical properties, causing difficulties for rolling due to brittleness.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Among the two types of silicon steel, grain-oriented (GO) and grain non-oriented (GNO), GO is most desirable for magnetic cores.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] It is anisotropic, offering better magnetic properties than GNO in one direction.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] As the magnetic field in inductor and transformer cores is always along the same direction, it is an advantage to use grain oriented steel in the preferred orientation.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Rotating machines, where the direction of the magnetic field can change, gain no benefit from grain-oriented steel.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] A family of specialized alloys exists for magnetic core applications.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Examples are mu-metal, permalloy, and supermalloy.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] They can be manufactured as stampings or as long ribbons for tape wound cores.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Sendust, are manufactured as powder and sintered to shape.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Many materials require careful heat treatment to reach their magnetic properties, and lose them when subjected to mechanical or thermal abuse.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] For example, the permeability of mu-metal increases about 40 times after annealing in hydrogen atmosphere in a magnetic field; subsequent sharper bends disrupt its grain alignment, leading to localized loss of permeability; this can be regained by repeating the annealing step.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Amorphous metal is a variety of alloys (e.g.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Metglas) that are non-crystalline or glassy.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] These are being used to create high-efficiency transformers.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The materials can be highly responsive to magnetic fields for low hysteresis losses, and they can also have lower conductivity to reduce eddy current losses.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Power utilities are currently making widespread use of these transformers for new installations.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] High mechanical strength and corrosion resistance are also common properties of metallic glasses which are positive for this application.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Powder cores consist of metal grains mixed with a suitable organic or inorganic binder, and pressed to desired density.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Higher density is achieved with higher pressure and lower amount of binder.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Higher density cores have higher permeability, but lower resistance and therefore higher losses due to eddy currents.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Finer particles allow operation at higher frequencies, as the eddy currents are mostly restricted to within the individual grains.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Coating of the particles with an insulating layer, or their separation with a thin layer of a binder, lowers the eddy current losses.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Presence of larger particles can degrade high-frequency performance.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Permeability is influenced by the spacing between the grains, which form distributed air gap; the less gap, the higher permeability and the less-soft saturation.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Due to large difference of densities, even a small amount of binder, weight-wise, can significantly increase the volume and therefore intergrain spacing.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Lower permeability materials are better suited for higher frequencies, due to balancing of core and winding losses.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The surface of the particles is often oxidized and coated with a phosphate layer, to provide them with mutual electrical insulation.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] It has higher core loss than the more advanced alloys, but this can be compensated for by making the core bigger; it is advantageous where cost is more important than mass and size.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Saturation flux of about 1 to 1.5 tesla.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Relatively high hysteresis and eddy current loss, operation limited to lower frequencies (approx. below 100 kHz).
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Used in energy storage inductors, DC output chokes, differential mode chokes, triac regulator chokes, chokes for power factor correction, resonant inductors, and pulse and flyback transformers.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The binder used is usually epoxy or other organic resin, susceptible to thermal aging.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] At higher temperatures, typically above 125 °C, the binder degrades and the core magnetic properties may change.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] With more heat-resistant binders the cores can be used up to 200 °C.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Iron powder cores are most commonly available as toroids.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Sometimes as E, EI, and rods or blocks, used primarily in high-power and high-current parts.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Carbonyl iron is significantly more expensive than hydrogen-reduced iron.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Powdered cores made of carbonyl iron, a highly pure iron, have high stability of parameters across a wide range of temperatures and magnetic flux levels, with excellent Q factors between 50 kHz and 200 MHz.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Carbonyl iron powders are basically constituted of micrometer-size spheres of iron coated in a thin layer of electrical insulation.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] This is equivalent to a microscopic laminated magnetic circuit (see silicon steel, above), hence reducing the eddy currents, particularly at very high frequencies.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Carbonyl iron has lower losses than hydrogen-reduced iron, but also lower permeability.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] A popular application of carbonyl iron-based magnetic cores is in high-frequency and broadband inductors and transformers, especially higher power ones.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Carbonyl iron cores are often called "RF cores".
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The as-prepared particles, "E-type"and have onion-like skin, with concentric shells separated with a gap.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] They contain significant amount of carbon.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] They behave as much smaller than what their outer size would suggest.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The "C-type" particles can be prepared by heating the E-type ones in hydrogen atmosphere at 400 °C for prolonged time, resulting in carbon-free powders.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Powdered cores made of hydrogen reduced iron have higher permeability but lower Q than carbonyl iron.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] They are used mostly for electromagnetic interference filters and low-frequency chokes, mainly in switched-mode power supplies.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Hydrogen-reduced iron cores are often called "power cores".
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] An alloy of about 2% molybdenum, 81% nickel, and 17% iron.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Very low core loss, low hysteresis and therefore low signal distortion.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Maximum saturation flux of about 0.8 tesla.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Used in high-Q filters, resonant circuits, loading coils, transformers, chokes, etc.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The material was first introduced in 1940, used in loading coils to compensate capacitance in long telephone lines.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] It is usable up to about 200 kHz to 1 MHz, depending on vendor.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] It is still used in above-ground telephone lines, due to its temperature stability.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Underground lines, where temperature is more stable, tend to use ferrite cores due to their lower cost.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] An alloy of about 50–50% of nickel and iron.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] High energy storage, saturation flux density of about 1.5 tesla.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Used in applications with high DC current bias (line noise filters, or inductors in switching regulators) or where low residual flux density is needed (e.g. pulse and flyback transformers, the high saturation is suitable for unipolar drive), especially where space is constrained.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The material is usable up to about 200 kHz.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] An alloy of 6% aluminium, 9% silicon, and 85% iron.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Very low magnetostriction, makes low audio noise.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Loses inductance with increasing temperature, unlike the other materials; can be exploited by combining with other materials as a composite core, for temperature compensation.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Used in switching power supplies, pulse and flyback transformers, in-line noise filters, swing chokes, and in filters in phase-fired controllers (e.g. dimmers) where low acoustic noise is important.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Absence of nickel results in easier processing of the material and its lower cost than both high-flux and MPP.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The material was invented in Japan in 1936.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] It is usable up to about 500 kHz to 1 MHz, depending on vendor.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] A nanocrystalline alloy of a standard iron-boron-silicon alloy, with addition of smaller amounts of copper and niobium.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The grain size of the powder reaches down to 10–100 nanometers.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The material has very good performance at lower frequencies.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] It is used in chokes for inverters and in high power applications.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Nanoperm, Vitroperm, Hitperm and Finemet.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Ferrite ceramics are used for high-frequency applications.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The ferrite materials can be engineered with a wide range of parameters.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] As ceramics, they are essentially insulators, which prevents eddy currents, although losses such as hysteresis losses can still occur.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] A coil not containing a magnetic core is called an *air core*.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] This includes coils wound on a plastic or ceramic form in addition to those made of stiff wire that are self-supporting and have air inside them.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Air core coils generally have a much lower inductance than similarly sized ferromagnetic core coils, but are used in radio frequency circuits to prevent energy losses called core losses that occur in magnetic cores.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The absence of normal core losses permits a higher Q factor, so air core coils are used in high frequency resonant circuits, such as up to a few megahertz.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] However, losses such as proximity effect and dielectric losses are still present.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Air cores are also used when field strengths above around 2 Tesla are required as they are not subject to saturation.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Most commonly made of ferrite or powdered iron, and used in radios especially for tuning an inductor.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The coil is wound around the rod, or a coil form with the rod inside.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Moving the rod in or out of the coil changes the flux through the coil, and can be used to adjust the inductance.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Often the rod is threaded to allow adjustment with a screwdriver.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] In radio circuits, a blob of wax or resin is used once the inductor has been tuned to prevent the core from moving.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The presence of the high permeability core increases the inductance, but the magnetic field lines must still pass through the air from one end of the rod to the other.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The air path ensures that the inductor remains linear.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] In this type of inductor radiation occurs at the end of the rod and electromagnetic interference may be a problem in some circumstances.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Like a cylindrical rod but is square, rarely used on its own.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] This type of core is most likely to be found in car ignition coils.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] E-shaped core are more symmetric solutions to form a closed magnetic system.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Most of the time, the electric circuit is wound around the center leg, whose section area is twice that of each individual outer leg.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] In 3-phase transformer cores, the legs are of equal size, and all three legs are wound.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Sheets of suitable iron stamped out in shapes like the (sans-serif) letters "E" and "I", are stacked with the "I" against the open end of the "E" to form a 3-legged structure.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Coils can be wound around any leg, but usually the center leg is used.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] This type of core is frequently used for power transformers, autotransformers, and inductors.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Similar to using an "E" and "I" together, a pair of "E" cores will accommodate a larger coil former and can produce a larger inductor or transformer.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] If an air gap is required, the centre leg of the "E" is shortened so that the air gap sits in the middle of the coil to minimize fringing and reduce electromagnetic interference.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] A planar core consists of two flat pieces of magnetic material, one above and one below the coil.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] It is typically used with a flat coil that is part of a printed circuit board.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] This design is excellent for mass production and allows a high power, small volume transformer to be constructed for low cost.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] It is not as ideal as either a **pot core** or **toroidal core** but costs less to produce.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] This is used for inductors and transformers.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The shape of a pot core is round with an internal hollow that almost completely encloses the coil.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Usually a pot core is made in two halves which fit together around a coil former (bobbin).
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] This design of core has a shielding effect, preventing radiation and reducing electromagnetic interference.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] This design is based on a toroid (the same shape as a doughnut).
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The coil is wound through the hole in the torus and around the outside.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] An ideal coil is distributed evenly all around the circumference of the torus.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The symmetry of this geometry creates a magnetic field of circular loops inside the core, and the lack of sharp bends will constrain virtually all of the field to the core material.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] This not only makes a highly efficient transformer, but also reduces the electromagnetic interference radiated by the coil.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] It is popular for applications where the desirable features are: high specific power per mass and volume, low mains hum, and minimal electromagnetic interference.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] One such application is the power supply for a hi-fi audio amplifier.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The main drawback that limits their use for general purpose applications is the inherent difficulty of winding wire through the center of a torus.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Unlike a split core (a core made of two elements, like a pair of *E* cores), specialized machinery is required for automated winding of a toroidal core.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Toroids have less audible noise, such as mains hum, because the magnetic forces do not exert bending moment on the core.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The core is only in compression or tension, and the circular shape is more stable mechanically.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The ring is essentially identical in shape and performance to the toroid, except that inductors commonly pass only through the center of the core, without wrapping around the core multiple times.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The ring core may also be composed of two separate C-shaped hemispheres secured together within a plastic shell, permitting it to be placed on finished cables with large connectors already installed, that would prevent threading the cable through the small inner diameter of a solid ring.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The AL value of a core configuration is frequently specified by manufacturers.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] where n is the number of turns, L is the inductance (e.g. in nH) and AL is expressed in inductance per turn squared (e.g. in nH/n2).
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] When the core is subjected to a *changing* magnetic field, as it is in devices that use AC current such as transformers, inductors, and AC motors and alternators, some of the power that would ideally be transferred through the device is lost in the core, dissipated as heat and sometimes noise.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Core loss is commonly termed *iron loss* in contradistinction to copper loss, the loss in the windings.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] When the magnetic field through the core changes, the magnetization of the core material changes by expansion and contraction of the tiny magnetic domains it is composed of, due to movement of the domain walls.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] This process causes losses, because the domain walls get "snagged" on defects in the crystal structure and then "snap" past them, dissipating energy as heat.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] It can be seen in the graph of the *B* field versus the *H* field for the material, which has the form of a closed loop.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] This equation shows that the amount of energy lost in the material in one cycle of the applied field is proportional to the area inside the hysteresis loop.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Since the energy lost in each cycle is constant, hysteresis power losses increase proportionally with frequency.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] If the core is electrically conductive, the changing magnetic field induces circulating loops of current in it, called eddy currents, due to electromagnetic induction.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The loops flow perpendicular to the magnetic field axis.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The energy of the currents is dissipated as heat in the resistance of the core material.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] The power loss is proportional to the area of the loops and inversely proportional to the resistivity of the core material.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Eddy current losses can be reduced by making the core out of thin laminations which have an insulating coating, or alternatively, making the core of a magnetic material with high electrical resistance, like ferrite.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Most magnetic cores intended for power converter application use ferrite cores for this reason.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] By definition, this category includes any losses in addition to eddy-current and hysteresis losses.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] This can also be described as broadening of the hysteresis loop with frequency.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Physical mechanisms for anomalous loss include localized eddy-current effects near moving domain walls.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] An equation known as Legg's equation models the magnetic material core loss at low flux densities.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Losses in magnetic materials can be characterized by the Steinmetz coefficients, which however do not take into account temperature variability.
[src:magnetic-core/magnetic-core] Material manufacturers provide data on core losses in tabular and graphical form for practical conditions of use.
